s\n | silver_year=2018\n | gold_button=yes\n | gold_year=2019\n | stats_update = March 2020\n}}\n|nationality=Indian|birth_place=Lucknow|status=Active}}\n'''Naman Mathur''' (born May 22, 1997), professionally known by his online alias '''MortaL''',<ref>{{cite web|title=YouTube channel of MortaL |url=https://www.youtube.com/channel/UC7Q7pl0z0MrdayvmAnchlJQ}}</ref> is an Indian [[YouTuber]], streamer, influencer and a gamer with over 4.3 million subscribers on [[Youtube]] and professional [[PlayerUnknown's Battlegrounds]] [[Esports]] Mobile player. He is known for streaming [[PlayerUnknown's Battlegrounds]] Mobile and is an active player in the esports community.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Mathur |first1=Naman |title=MortaL |url=https://liquipedia.net/pubg/Mortal |website=Liquipedia PlayerUnknown's Battleground |publisher=PUBG Esport Managers |accessdate=11 March 2020}}</ref> Naman has verified [[Instagram]] Handle<ref name=\"@ig_mortal\">{{cite web |last1=Mathur |first1=Naman |title=MortaL's Instagram page |url=https://www.instagram.com/ig_mortal/?hl=en}}</ref> with over 1.5 million followers.\n\n== YouTube career ==\nPrior to becoming a full-time [[Online streamer|streamer]], Naman started his [[YouTube]] career in 2015 by uploading various gameplay videos of a Mobile game Mini Militia. He had a casual approach towards gaming and uploading YouTube videos without any plans of stepping into the industry. In March 2018, a new mobile version of game [[PlayerUnknown's Battlegrounds]] flooded the gaming scenario and became very popular among mobile gamers. MortaL soon began uploading content of [[PlayerUnknown's Battlegrounds]] Mobile. He achieved quick popularity when one of his videos<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Eul0ePFkHyw|title= One of the Videos of MortaL clutching at last second}}</ref> went viral. Within a short period of time, his videos gathered millions of views. Apart from the uploads, MortaL is also a full-time Pubg Mobile streamer. At present, MortaL has over 4.35 million Subscribers on YouTube.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=PY0e0OG3rv4|title= Video of MortaL with over 11 million views on Youtube}}</ref>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n!Date\n!YouTube Subscriber Milestones\n|-\n|2018-11-01\n|100,000 Subscribers\n|-\n|2019-01-08\n|500,000 Subscribers\n|-\n|2019-02-19\n|1,000,000 Subscribers\n|-\n|2019-05-07\n|2,000,000 Subscribers\n|-\n|2019-09-17\n|3,000,000 Subscribers\n|-\n|2020-02-25\n|4,000,000 Subscribers\n|}\n\n== Individual Records ==\n*In March 2020, in a collaborative battle between MortaL and CarryMinati ([[Ajey Nagar]]), MortaL achieved the peak of 178,296 Live Viewers on his stream, whereas CarryMinati achieved peak of 207,000 Live Viewers on his Stream. The peak number of live Viewers for the battle were 350,000 thus creating the record of having the highest number of Live Audience for an event for Individual Gaming Creators in the country.\n*Before this event in Nov 2019, MortaL was 3rd highest cross-platform among all over the world. Professional Gaming Head [[Ryan Wyatt]] himself, tweeted about this Record, Congratulating the top Influencers. Twitch streamers, The Grefg and [[Vegetta777]] currently hold First and Second Spot Respectively, whereas MortaL holds the Third Place, was the only Indian to enter the chart.\n*At present according to [[Social Blade]], MortaL holds the record of having highest audience responsive streams in the country for the Category: [[esports|Gaming]] with 1,006,390 daily views (According to March 2020) in the platform [[YouTube]]. All statistics considered from site SocialBlade. While considering globally, Jelly holds the first place in terms of Daily Views. Whereas MortaL holds the rank 6th just behind other top Influencers like [[PewDiePie]], Kwebbelkop, VanossGaming and [[Ninja (video game player)|Ninja]].\n\n== Esports career ==\nInitially MortaL played with his clanmates and ingame friends. In December 2018, he decided to form a professional [[Roster (workplace)|Roster]] his teammates for PUBG [[Esports]] and named the team as 'SOUL'.\n\n[[File:Soul winning PMIS 2018 Hyderabad.jpeg]]\n\nTeam SOUL participated in the popular [[LAN]] event tournament named [[DreamHack]] and secured 1st position in the tournament for the game PlayerUnknown's Battlegrounds [[wikt:Mobile|Mobile]].\nSoon, the team began improving the gameplay and synergy while preparing for a Major PlayerUnknown's Battlegrounds Mobile tournament Pubg Mobile India Series in March 2019 [[Hyderabad]] with over a price pool of US$140,000. Eventually, Team SOUL secured 1st place in the tournament winning the amount of US$41,000.<ref>{{cite web |title=Results of PMIS posted on Official sources |url=https://liquipedia.net/pubg/PUBG_Mobile_India_Series/2019|website=Liquipedia PlayerUnknown's Battleground |publisher=PUBG Esport Official Staff |accessdate=11 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=SouL wins PMIS|url=https://indianexpress.com/article/technology/gaming/pubg-mobile-india-series-2019-team-soul-wins-tournament-30-lakh-prize-money-5620246/|website=Indian Express|publisher=Indian Express}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=The Tournament was streamed live|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=x_a0qHf67MA}}</ref>\n\nIn June 2019, at another major event Pubg Mobile Club Open Team SOUL were placed first in the following tournament<ref>{{cite web |title=Results of PMCO Spring Split Regional Finals posted on Official sources |url=https://liquipedia.net/pubg/PUBG_Mobile_Club_Open/Spring/2019/India |website=Liquipedia PlayerUnknown's Battleground |publisher=PUBG Esport Official Staff |accessdate=11 March 2020}}</ref> winning amount of US$50,000 and the qualification for the Global Finals in [[Berlin]]. At the Berlin Finals, Team SOUL acquired 12th position.\n\n\n[[File: Team SouL at Berlin 2019.jpeg]]\n\n\n<ref>{{cite web |title= Results at Official PUBG Mobile Esports site|url=https://liquipedia.net/pubg/PUBG_Mobile_Club_Open/Spring/2019|website=Liquipedia PlayerUnknown's Battleground |publisher=PUBG Esport Official Staff |accessdate=11 March 2020}}</ref> In the Second season of Pubg Mobile Club Open, Team SOUL finished as runner-ups <ref>{{cite web |title=Results of PMCO Fall Split Regional Finals posted on Official sources |url=https://liquipedia.net/pubg/PUBG_Mobile_Club_Open/Fall/2019/India |website=Liquipedia PlayerUnknown's Battleground |publisher=PUBG Esport Official Staff |accessdate=11 March 2020}}</ref>\nin the Regional Finals, and ultimately 12th position again<ref>{{cite web |title=Results at Official PUBG Mobile Esports site|url=https://liquipedia.net/pubg/PUBG_Mobile_Club_Open/Fall/2019|website=Liquipedia PlayerUnknown's Battleground |publisher=PUBG Esport Official Staff |accessdate=11 March 2020}}</ref> in Global Finals in [[Kuala Lumpur]]\n\n== Owned Team(s) ==\n\n*'''Team SouL-'''\n[[File:Logo of team soul 2019.png]]\n\nNaman 'MortaL' Mathur is the owner of [[PlayerUnknown's Battleground]] Mobile's [[Esport]] team named as '''Team SouL'''. The Team was formed back in Late 2018 for the [[LAN]] tournament [[DreamHack]] Mumbai 2018.\nOver the time there were many changes across the Roster. MortaL, apart from being the owner of team, also plays for the team. Under the leadership of MortaL, Team SouL consecutively won two National Level Tournaments - PUBG Mobile India Series and PUBG Mobile Club Open. All the best teams across the nation competed for it (Qualifier through basis) and Team SouL won both the cups. Thus, making Team SouL the team with Most Winning Titles in the Country.\n\n'''Current Roster-'''\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n!Player ID\n!Name\n!Role\n!Join Date\n|-\n|Mortal\n|Naman Mathur\n|IGL Filter, Assaulter/sniper<br />\n|2018\n|-\n|Viper\n|Yash Soni\n|Support\n|2018\n|-\n|ReGaLToS\n|Parv Singh\n|Assaulter and Entry fragger\n|2019\n|-\n|Aman\n|Aman Jain\n|Assaulter\n|2019<br />\n|-\n|Sangwan\n|Dhruv Sangwan\n|I.G.L\n|2020\n|}\n\n'''Former Players-'''\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n!Player ID\n!Name\n!Role\n!Duration\n|-\n|Slayer\n|Kanishk Shah\n|Sniper\n|2018\u20132019\n|-\n|Owais\n|Mohammed Owais Lakhani\n|IGL, Entry Fragger\n|2018\u20132019\n|-\n|Ronak\n|Harpreet Singh Janjhua\n|Sniper, Middle Man\n|2018\u20132019\n|-\n|Sc0ut\n|Tanmay Singh\n|IGL Filter, Assaulter\n|2019-2019\n|-\n|ClutchGod\n|Vivek Abhas Horo\n|Assaulter\n|2019-2019\n|}\n\n'''Roster Timeline-'''\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n!Date\n!Player In\n!Player Out\n!Roster\n|-\n|2018-12-20\n|  +Ronak\n+Owais\n\n+VipeR\n\n+Slayer\n|\n|MortaL, Owais, Ronak, VipeR, Slayer\n|-\n|2019-08-05\n| +Sc0ut\n| -MortaL\n-Slayer\n|Sc0ut, VipeR, Ronak, Owais\n|-\n|2019-08-15\n|\n| -Sc0ut\n-Owais\n\n-Ronak\n|VipeR\n|-\n|2019-08-28\n| +Frost\n+Regaltos\n\n+MortaL\n|\n|MortaL, VipeR, Regaltos, Frost\n|-\n|2019-10-13\n| +ClutchGod\n| -Frost\n|MortaL, VipeR, Regaltos, ClutchGod\n|-\n|2019-11-10\n| +Aman\n| -ClutchGod\n|MortaL, VipeR, Regaltos, Aman\n|-\n|2019-01-11\n| +Sangwan\n|\n|MortaL, VipeR, Regaltos, Aman, Sangwan\n|}\n\n== Tournament Standings ==\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n!Date\n!Placement\n!Tier\n! Tournament\n!Prize\n|-\n|2018-12-22\n|1st\n|Premier\n|DreamHack Mumbai 2018\n|\u20b920,000\n|-\n|2019-03-10\n|1st\n|Major\n|PUBG Mobile India Series<ref>{{cite web |title=Results of PMIS posted on Official sources |url=https://liquipedia.net/pubg/PUBG_Mobile_India_Series/2019|website=Liquipedia PlayerUnknown's Battleground |publisher=PUBG Esport Official Staff |accessdate=11 March 2020}}</ref>\n|$42,000\n|-\n|2019-06-15\n|1st\n|Major\n|PUBG Mobile Club Open Spring Split South Asia<ref>{{cite web |title=Results of PMCO Spring Split Regional Finals posted on Official sources |url=https://liquipedia.net/pubg/PUBG_Mobile_Club_Open/Spring/2019/India|website=Liquipedia PlayerUnknown's Battleground |publisher=PUBG Esport Official Staff |accessdate=11 March 2020}}</ref>\n|$60,000\n|-\n|2019-07-28\n|12th\n|Global\n|PUBG Mobile Club Open Spring Split Global Finals<ref>{{cite web |title= Results at Official PUBG Mobile Esports site|url=https://liquipedia.net/pubg/PUBG_Mobile_Club_Open/Spring/2019|website=Liquipedia PlayerUnknown's Battleground |publisher=PUBG Esport Official Staff |accessdate=11 March 2020}}</ref>\n|$2,500\n|-\n|2019-09-29\n|13th\n|Invitational \n|PUBG Mobile Star Challenge- Taiwan<ref>{{cite web |title= Results at Official PUBG Mobile Esports site|url=https://liquipedia.net/pubg/PUBG_Mobile_Star_Challenge/2019|website=Liquipedia PlayerUnknown's Battleground |publisher=PUBG Esport Official Staff |accessdate=11 March 2020}}</ref>\n|$3,000\n|-\n|2019-11-10\n|2nd\n|Major\n|PUBG Mobile Club Open Fall Split South Asia<ref>{{cite web |title=Results of PMCO Fall Split Regional Finals posted on Official sources |url=https://liquipedia.net/pubg/PUBG_Mobile_Club_Open/Fall/2019/India |website=Liquipedia PlayerUnknown's Battleground |publisher=PUBG Esport Official Staff |accessdate=11 March 2020}}</ref>\n|$30,000\n|-\n|2019-12-01\n|12th\n|Global\n|PUBG Mobile Club Open Fall Split Global Finals<ref>{{cite web |title=Results at Official PUBG Mobile Esports site|url=https://liquipedia.net/pubg/PUBG_Mobile_Club_Open/Fall/2019|website=Liquipedia PlayerUnknown's Battleground |publisher=PUBG Esport Official Staff |accessdate=11 March 2020}}</ref>\n|$8,000\n|-\n|2019-12-29\n|12th\n|Invitational\n|PeaceKeeper Elite Championship- Beijing<ref>{{cite web |title=Results at Official PUBG Mobile Esports site|url=https://liquipedia.net/pubg/Peacekeeper_Elite_Championship/2019|website=Liquipedia PlayerUnknown's Battleground |publisher=PUBG Esport Official Staff |accessdate=11 March 2020}}</ref>\n|$6,425\n|}\n\n== Personal life and collaborations ==\nMathur currently lives in [[Mumbai]], [[India]] but is from [[Lucknow]]. Raised by single parent since an early age, Mathur's family consists of his mother Kavita Mathur and brother Abhinav Mathur. Mathur completed his [[Bachelor of Commerce]] (B.Com) Degree from South Indian Education Society ([[SIES Nerul]]).  Mathur has collaborated with various personalities across the country like [[Vicky Kaushal]]<ref name=\"MortaL with Vicky Kaushal\">{{cite web |title=MortaL with Vicky Kaushal|last1=Mehndiratta |first1=Rahul |url=https://essenceglobal.com/article/pubg-india-the-new-marketingchannel |website=Essence News |publisher=Essence News |accessdate=11 March 2020}}</ref> for the promotion of [[Uri: The Surgical Strike]], [[Manoj Bajpayee]]<ref name=\"MortaL with Manoj Baypayee\">{{cite web |title=MortaL with Manoj Bajpayee|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=FGT94Bhtbn4 |website=YouTube |publisher=Amazon Prime Video India |accessdate=11 March 2020}}</ref> for the webseries [[The Family Man (Indian TV series)]] and with [[Tiger Shroff]].<ref name=\"MortaL with Actor Tiger Shroff\">{{cite web |title=MortaL with Tiger Shroff|url=https://www.instagram.com/p/B9g76leFAen/ |website=Instagram.com |publisher=Naman Mathur |accessdate=11 March 2020}}</ref> In 2019, MortaL appeared on the index cover of MensXP <ref name=\"MortaL as Digital Disruptor for [[MensXP]]\">{{cite web |title=mortal appearing on index of MensXP cover|url=https://www.mensxp.com/digital-cover/digital-disruptors-2019.html |publisher=MensXP}}</ref> as a Digital Disruptor. In December 2019, Mathur was invited for the opening ceremony of the Mobile Accessory Store of the digit products company-'[[OnePlus]]' in [[Kalyan]] (Navi Mumbai) which also served as huge fan-meet event for his followers.\n\n== Contribution towards community ==\nApart from Professional life, Mathur has been actively involved for the betterment of community. Today, being the top most influencer of gaming in India, MortaL has always been an idol for many new content creators to make their debut into the Gaming. Socially, Mathur helped to raise funds with his charity streams on the aftermath of various incidents for the victims of [[2019 Pulwama attack]],<ref>{{cite web |title=MortaL does Charity Stream to raise funds for Pulwana Attack Tragedy |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=aPMEgfDKmAc |website=YouTube |accessdate=12 March 2020}}</ref> [[2019 Bihar floods]] refugees,<ref name=\"Sources- From YouTube\">{{cite web |title=Charity Stream which MortaL did for the Bihar Flood Refugees |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=fz1X-krljiM |website=YouTube |accessdate=12 March 2020}}</ref> for Assam flood refugees<ref>{{cite news |title=Mathur does charity Stream for Assam Flood Refugees |url=https://www.guwahatiplus.com/daily-news/pubg-player-mortal-streams-match-to-raise-funds-for-assam-floods |accessdate=12 March 2020 |agency=News Article |publisher=Guwahati Plus}}</ref> & even for the [[Bushfires in Australia]].<ref>{{cite web |title=MortaL does Charity stream to raise funds for Australian Bush Fires |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=o4WdeZ7OSRE |website=YouTube |accessdate=12 March 2020}}</ref>\nMathur even donated his share of winning prize<ref>{{cite news |title=Naman Mathur Donates Prize money to the Army |url=https://www.news18.com/news/tech/pubg-mobile-club-open-2019-soul-mortal-donates-entire-winning-amount-to-indian-army-2383393.html |accessdate=12 March 2020 |agency=News |publisher=News18}}</ref> ($7,500) to the [[Indian Army]] he won after securing Runner-up place in the PUBG Mobile Club Open Fall Split SA Finals 2019.<ref>{{cite web |title=Results of PMCO Fall Split Regional Finals posted on Official sources |url=https://liquipedia.net/pubg/PUBG_Mobile_Club_Open/Fall/2019/India |website=Liquipedia PlayerUnknown's Battleground |publisher=PUBG Esport Official Staff |accessdate=11 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Social Media Handles==\n\n*[https://www.instagram.com/ig_mortal/?hl=en MortaL] on Instagram\n*[https://www.facebook.com/Soul-MortaL-PUBG-Mobile-561089750986134/ MortaL] on Facebook\n*[https://twitter.com/Mortal04907880 MortaL] on Twitter\n*[https://www.youtube.com/channel/UC7Q7pl0z0MrdayvmAnchlJQ MortaL] on YouTube\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:1996 births]]\n[[Category:Indian YouTubers]]\n[[Category:Indian esports players]]\n[[Category:Male YouTubers]]\n", "text_old": "{{Multiple issues|{{copy edit|date=April 2020}}{{peacock|date=April 2020}}{{autobiography|date=April 2020}}}}\n\n\n{{short description|Indian esports player}}\n{{Infobox Pro Gaming player\n| ID         = MortaL\n| name       = Naman Sandeep Mathur\n| image      = MortaL at PMCO 2019.jpg \n| caption    = \n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|1997|5|22}}\n| hometown   = [[Mumbai, India]]\n| games      = ''[[PlayerUnknown's Battlegrounds]]''\n| earnings   = \n| team1      = Plays for Team SouL<ref>{{cite web |title=Information about team Soul on official PUBG esports site|url=https://liquipedia.net/pubg/Team_SouL}}</ref>\n| highlights = \n\u2022DreamHack Mumbai 2018 Champions\n\n\u2022PUBG Mobile India Series 2019 Champions<ref>{{cite web |title=Results of PMIS posted on Official sources |url=https://liquipedia.net/pubg/PUBG_Mobile_India_Series/2019|website=Liquipedia PlayerUnknown's Battleground |publisher=PUBG Esport Official Staff |accessdate=11 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n\u2022PUBG Mobile Club Open Spring Split SA 2019 Champions<ref>{{cite web |title=Results of PMCO Spring Split Regional Finals posted on Official sources |url=https://liquipedia.net/pubg/PUBG_Mobile_Club_Open/Spring/2019/India|website=Liquipedia PlayerUnknown's Battleground |publisher=PUBG Esport Official Staff |accessdate=11 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n\u2022PUBG Mobile Club Open Fall Split SA 2019 Runner-ups<ref>{{cite web |title=Results of PMCO Fall Split Regional Finals posted on Official sources |url=https://liquipedia.net/pubg/PUBG_Mobile_Club_Open/Fall/2019/India |website=Liquipedia PlayerUnknown's Battleground |publisher=PUBG Esport Official Staff |accessdate=11 March 2020}}</ref>\n| module2    = {{Infobox YouTube personality\n | subbox = yes\n | channel_display_name=MortaL\n | channel_direct_url=/channel/UC7Q7pl0z0MrdayvmAnchlJQ\n | genre= [[Competitive gaming]]\n | years_active=2015\u2013present\n | subscribers=4.34 million\n | views=413 million\n | silver_button=yes\n | silver_year=2018\n | gold_button=yes\n | gold_year=2019\n | stats_update = March 2020\n}}\n|nationality=Indian|birth_place=Lucknow|status=Active}}\n'''Naman Mathur''' (born May 22, 1997), professionally known by his online alias '''MortaL''',<ref>{{cite web|title=YouTube channel of MortaL |url=https://www.youtube.com/channel/UC7Q7pl0z0MrdayvmAnchlJQ}}</ref> is an Indian [[YouTuber]], streamer, influencer and a gamer with over 4.3 million subscribers on [[Youtube]] and professional [[PlayerUnknown's Battlegrounds]] [[Esports]] Mobile player. He is known for streaming [[PlayerUnknown's Battlegrounds]] Mobile and is an active player in the esports community.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Mathur |first1=Naman |title=MortaL |url=https://liquipedia.net/pubg/Mortal |website=Liquipedia PlayerUnknown's Battleground |publisher=PUBG Esport Managers |accessdate=11 March 2020}}</ref> Naman has verified [[Instagram]] Handle<ref name=\"@ig_mortal\">{{cite web |last1=Mathur |first1=Naman |title=MortaL's Instagram page |url=https://www.instagram.com/ig_mortal/?hl=en}}</ref> with over 1.5 million followers.\n\n== YouTube career ==\nPrior to becoming a full-time [[Online streamer|streamer]], Naman started his [[YouTube]] career in 2015 by uploading various gameplay videos of a Mobile game Mini Militia. He had a casual approach towards gaming and uploading YouTube videos without any plans of stepping into the industry. In March 2018, a new mobile version of game [[PlayerUnknown's Battlegrounds]] flooded the gaming scenario and became very popular among mobile gamers. MortaL soon began uploading content of [[PlayerUnknown's Battlegrounds]] Mobile. He achieved quick popularity when one of his videos<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Eul0ePFkHyw|title= One of the Videos of MortaL clutching at last second}}</ref> went viral. Within a short period of time, his videos gathered millions of views. Apart from the uploads, MortaL is also a full-time Pubg Mobile streamer. At present, MortaL has over 4.35 million Subscribers on YouTube.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=PY0e0OG3rv4|title= Video of MortaL with over 11 million views on Youtube}}</ref>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n!Date\n!YouTube Subscriber Milestones\n|-\n|2018-11-01\n|100,000 Subscribers\n|-\n|2019-01-08\n|500,000 Subscribers\n|-\n|2019-02-19\n|1,000,000 Subscribers\n|-\n|2019-05-07\n|2,000,000 Subscribers\n|-\n|2019-09-17\n|3,000,000 Subscribers\n|-\n|2020-02-25\n|4,000,000 Subscribers\n|}\n\n== Individual Records ==\n*In March 2020, in a collaborative battle between MortaL and CarryMinati ([[Ajey Nagar]]), MortaL achieved the peak of 178,296 Live Viewers on his stream, whereas CarryMinati achieved peak of 207,000 Live Viewers on his Stream. The peak number of live Viewers for the battle were 350,000 thus creating the record of having the highest number of Live Audience for an event for Individual Gaming Creators in the country.\n*Before this event in Nov 2019, MortaL was 3rd highest cross-platform among all over the world. Professional Gaming Head [[Ryan Wyatt]] himself, tweeted about this Record, Congratulating the top Influencers. Twitch streamers, The Grefg and [[Vegetta777]] currently hold First and Second Spot Respectively, whereas MortaL holds the Third Place, was the only Indian to enter the chart.\n*At present according to [[Social Blade]], MortaL holds the record of having highest audience responsive streams in the country for the Category: [[esports|Gaming]] with 1,006,390 daily views (According to March 2020) in the platform [[YouTube]]. All statistics considered from site SocialBlade. While considering globally, Jelly holds the first place in terms of Daily Views. Whereas MortaL holds the rank 6th just behind other top Influencers like [[PewDiePie]], Kwebbelkop, VanossGaming and [[Ninja (video game player)|Ninja]].\n\n== Esports career ==\nInitially MortaL played with his clanmates and ingame friends. In December 2018, he decided to form a professional [[Roster (workplace)|Roster]] his teammates for PUBG [[Esports]] and named the team as 'SOUL'.\n\n[[File:Soul winning PMIS 2018 Hyderabad.jpeg]]\n\nTeam SOUL participated in the popular [[LAN]] event tournament named [[DreamHack]] and secured 1st position in the tournament for the game PlayerUnknown's Battlegrounds [[wikt:Mobile|Mobile]].\nSoon, the team began improving the gameplay and synergy while preparing for a Major PlayerUnknown's Battlegrounds Mobile tournament Pubg Mobile India Series in March 2019 [[Hyderabad]] with over a price pool of US$140,000. Eventually, Team SOUL secured 1st place in the tournament winning the amount of US$41,000.<ref>{{cite web |title=Results of PMIS posted on Official sources |url=https://liquipedia.net/pubg/PUBG_Mobile_India_Series/2019|website=Liquipedia PlayerUnknown's Battleground |publisher=PUBG Esport Official Staff |accessdate=11 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=SouL wins PMIS|url=https://indianexpress.com/article/technology/gaming/pubg-mobile-india-series-2019-team-soul-wins-tournament-30-lakh-prize-money-5620246/|website=Indian Express|publisher=Indian Express}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=The Tournament was streamed live|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=x_a0qHf67MA}}</ref>\n\nIn June 2019, at another major event Pubg Mobile Club Open Team SOUL were placed first in the following tournament<ref>{{cite web |title=Results of PMCO Spring Split Regional Finals posted on Official sources |url=https://liquipedia.net/pubg/PUBG_Mobile_Club_Open/Spring/2019/India |website=Liquipedia PlayerUnknown's Battleground |publisher=PUBG Esport Official Staff |accessdate=11 March 2020}}</ref> winning amount of US$50,000 and the qualification for the Global Finals in [[Berlin]]. At the Berlin Finals, Team SOUL acquired 12th position.\n\n\n[[File: Team SouL at Berlin 2019.jpeg]]\n\n\n<ref>{{cite web |title= Results at Official PUBG Mobile Esports site|url=https://liquipedia.net/pubg/PUBG_Mobile_Club_Open/Spring/2019|website=Liquipedia PlayerUnknown's Battleground |publisher=PUBG Esport Official Staff |accessdate=11 March 2020}}</ref> In the Second season of Pubg Mobile Club Open, Team SOUL finished as runner-ups <ref>{{cite web |title=Results of PMCO Fall Split Regional Finals posted on Official sources |url=https://liquipedia.net/pubg/PUBG_Mobile_Club_Open/Fall/2019/India |website=Liquipedia PlayerUnknown's Battleground |publisher=PUBG Esport Official Staff |accessdate=11 March 2020}}</ref>\nin the Regional Finals, and ultimately 12th position again<ref>{{cite web |title=Results at Official PUBG Mobile Esports site|url=https://liquipedia.net/pubg/PUBG_Mobile_Club_Open/Fall/2019|website=Liquipedia PlayerUnknown's Battleground |publisher=PUBG Esport Official Staff |accessdate=11 March 2020}}</ref> in Global Finals in [[Kuala Lumpur]]\n\n== Owned Team(s) ==\n\n*'''Team SouL-'''\n[[File:Logo of team soul 2019.png]]\n\nNaman 'MortaL' Mathur is the owner of [[PlayerUnknown's Battleground]] Mobile's [[Esport]] team named as '''Team SouL'''. The Team was formed back in Late 2018 for the [[LAN]] tournament [[DreamHack]] Mumbai 2018.\nOver the time there were many changes across the Roster. MortaL, apart from being the owner of team, also plays for the team. Under the leadership of MortaL, Team SouL consecutively won two National Level Tournaments - PUBG Mobile India Series and PUBG Mobile Club Open. All the best teams across the nation competed for it (Qualifier through basis) and Team SouL won both the cups. Thus, making Team SouL the team with Most Winning Titles in the Country.\n\n'''Current Roster-'''\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n!Player ID\n!Name\n!Role\n!Join Date\n|-\n|Mortal\n|Naman Mathur\n|IGL Filter, Assaulter/sniper<br />\n|2018\n|-\n|Viper\n|Yash Soni\n|Support\n|2018\n|-\n|ReGaLToS\n|Parv Singh\n|Assaulter and Entry fragger\n|2019\n|-\n|Aman\n|Aman Jain\n|Assaulter\n|2019<br />\n|-\n|Sangwan\n|Dhruv Sangwan\n|I.G.L\n|2020\n|}\n\n'''Former Players-'''\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n!Player ID\n!Name\n!Role\n!Duration\n|-\n|Slayer\n|Kanishk Shah\n|Sniper\n|2018\u20132019\n|-\n|Owais\n|Mohammed Owais Lakhani\n|IGL, Entry Fragger\n|2018\u20132019\n|-\n|Ronak\n|Harpreet Singh Janjhua\n|Sniper, Middle Man\n|2018\u20132019\n|-\n|Sc0ut\n|Tanmay Singh\n|IGL Filter, Assaulter\n|2019-2019\n|-\n|ClutchGod\n|Vivek Abhas Horo\n|Assaulter\n|2019-2019\n|}\n\n'''Roster Timeline-'''\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n!Date\n!Player In\n!Player Out\n!Roster\n|-\n|2018-12-20\n|  +Ronak\n+Owais\n\n+VipeR\n\n+Slayer\n|\n|MortaL, Owais, Ronak, VipeR, Slayer\n|-\n|2019-08-05\n| +Sc0ut\n| -MortaL\n-Slayer\n|Sc0ut, VipeR, Ronak, Owais\n|-\n|2019-08-15\n|\n| -Sc0ut\n-Owais\n\n-Ronak\n|VipeR\n|-\n|2019-08-28\n| +Frost\n+Regaltos\n\n+MortaL\n|\n|MortaL, VipeR, Regaltos, Frost\n|-\n|2019-10-13\n| +ClutchGod\n| -Frost\n|MortaL, VipeR, Regaltos, ClutchGod\n|-\n|2019-11-10\n| +Aman\n| -ClutchGod\n|MortaL, VipeR, Regaltos, Aman\n|-\n|2019-01-11\n| +Sangwan\n|\n|MortaL, VipeR, Regaltos, Aman, Sangwan\n|}\n\n== Tournament Standings ==\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n!Date\n!Placement\n!Tier\n! Tournament\n!Prize\n|-\n|2018-12-22\n|1st\n|Premier\n|DreamHack Mumbai 2018\n|\u20b920,000\n|-\n|2019-03-10\n|1st\n|Major\n|PUBG Mobile India Series<ref>{{cite web |title=Results of PMIS posted on Official sources |url=https://liquipedia.net/pubg/PUBG_Mobile_India_Series/2019|website=Liquipedia PlayerUnknown's Battleground |publisher=PUBG Esport Official Staff |accessdate=11 March 2020}}</ref>\n|$42,000\n|-\n|2019-06-15\n|1st\n|Major\n|PUBG Mobile Club Open Spring Split South Asia<ref>{{cite web |title=Results of PMCO Spring Split Regional Finals posted on Official sources |url=https://liquipedia.net/pubg/PUBG_Mobile_Club_Open/Spring/2019/India|website=Liquipedia PlayerUnknown's Battleground |publisher=PUBG Esport Official Staff |accessdate=11 March 2020}}</ref>\n|$60,000\n|-\n|2019-07-28\n|