 of Commerce]] (B.Com) Degree from South Indian Education Society ([[SIES Nerul]]).  Mathur has collaborated with various personalities across the country like [[Vicky Kaushal]]<ref name=\"MortaL with Vicky Kaushal\">{{cite web |title=MortaL with Vicky Kaushal|last1=Mehndiratta |first1=Rahul |url=https://essenceglobal.com/article/pubg-india-the-new-marketingchannel |website=Essence News |publisher=Essence News |accessdate=11 March 2020}}</ref> for the promotion of [[Uri: The Surgical Strike]], [[Manoj Bajpayee]]<ref name=\"MortaL with Manoj Baypayee\">{{cite web |title=MortaL with Manoj Bajpayee|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=FGT94Bhtbn4 |website=YouTube |publisher=Amazon Prime Video India |accessdate=11 March 2020}}</ref> for the webseries [[The Family Man (Indian TV series)]] and with [[Tiger Shroff]].<ref name=\"MortaL with Actor Tiger Shroff\">{{cite web |title=MortaL with Tiger Shroff|url=https://www.instagram.com/p/B9g76leFAen/ |website=Instagram.com |publisher=Naman Mathur |accessdate=11 March 2020}}</ref> In 2019, MortaL appeared on the index cover of MensXP <ref name=\"MortaL as Digital Disruptor for [[MensXP]]\">{{cite web |title=mortal appearing on index of MensXP cover|url=https://www.mensxp.com/digital-cover/digital-disruptors-2019.html |publisher=MensXP}}</ref> as a Digital Disruptor. In December 2019, Mathur was invited for the opening ceremony of the Mobile Accessory Store of the digit products company-'[[OnePlus]]' in [[Kalyan]] (Navi Mumbai) which also served as huge fan-meet event for his followers.\n\n== Contribution towards community ==\nApart from Professional life, Mathur has been actively involved for the betterment of community. Today, being the top most influencer of gaming in India, MortaL has always been an idol for many new content creators to make their debut into the Gaming. Socially, Mathur helped to raise funds with his charity streams on the aftermath of various incidents for the victims of [[2019 Pulwama attack]],<ref>{{cite web |title=MortaL does Charity Stream to raise funds for Pulwana Attack Tragedy |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=aPMEgfDKmAc |website=YouTube |accessdate=12 March 2020}}</ref> [[2019 Bihar floods]] refugees,<ref name=\"Sources- From YouTube\">{{cite web |title=Charity Stream which MortaL did for the Bihar Flood Refugees |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=fz1X-krljiM |website=YouTube |accessdate=12 March 2020}}</ref> for Assam flood refugees<ref>{{cite news |title=Mathur does charity Stream for Assam Flood Refugees |url=https://www.guwahatiplus.com/daily-news/pubg-player-mortal-streams-match-to-raise-funds-for-assam-floods |accessdate=12 March 2020 |agency=News Article |publisher=Guwahati Plus}}</ref> & even for the [[Bushfires in Australia]].<ref>{{cite web |title=MortaL does Charity stream to raise funds for Australian Bush Fires |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=o4WdeZ7OSRE |website=YouTube |accessdate=12 March 2020}}</ref>\nMathur even donated his share of winning prize<ref>{{cite news |title=Naman Mathur Donates Prize money to the Army |url=https://www.news18.com/news/tech/pubg-mobile-club-open-2019-soul-mortal-donates-entire-winning-amount-to-indian-army-2383393.html |accessdate=12 March 2020 |agency=News |publisher=News18}}</ref> ($7,500) to the [[Indian Army]] he won after securing Runner-up place in the PUBG Mobile Club Open Fall Split SA Finals 2019.<ref>{{cite web |title=Results of PMCO Fall Split Regional Finals posted on Official sources |url=https://liquipedia.net/pubg/PUBG_Mobile_Club_Open/Fall/2019/India |website=Liquipedia PlayerUnknown's Battleground |publisher=PUBG Esport Official Staff |accessdate=11 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Social Media Handles==\n\n*[https://www.instagram.com/ig_mortal/?hl=en MortaL] on Instagram\n*[https://www.facebook.com/Soul-MortaL-PUBG-Mobile-561089750986134/ MortaL] on Facebook\n*[https://twitter.com/Mortal04907880 MortaL] on Twitter\n*[https://www.youtube.com/channel/UC7Q7pl0z0MrdayvmAnchlJQ MortaL] on YouTube\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:1996 births]]\n[[Category:Indian YouTubers]]\n[[Category:Indian esports players]]\n[[Category:Male YouTubers]]\n", "name_user": "27.59.181.199", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/MortaL_(streamer)"}
{"title_page": "Marshall Allen", "text_new": "{{for|the American journalist|Marshall Allen (journalist)}}\n{{Infobox musical artist <!-- See Wikipedia:WikiProject Musicians -->\n| name                = Marshall Allen\n| image                 = Marshall Allen.jpg\n| caption            = Photo of Marshall Allen by Seth Tisue\n| image_size            = \n| background          = non_vocal_instrumentalist\n| birth_name          = Marshall Allen\n| alias               = \n| birth_date                = {{Birth date and age|1924|5|25}} \n| death_date                = \n| origin              = [[Louisville, Kentucky]], United States\n| instrument          = [[Saxophone]], [[flute]], [[oboe]], [[piccolo]], [[EWI (musical instrument)|EVI]]\n| genre               = [[Jazz]]\n| occupation          = \n| years_active        = \n| label               = \n| associated_acts     = [[Sun Ra]], [[Paul Bley]]\n| website                 = \n| current_members     = \n| past_members        = \n}}\n'''Marshall Belford Allen''' (born May 25, 1924) is an American [[free jazz]] and [[avant-garde jazz]] [[alto saxophone]] player.<ref name=\"RCJE\">{{Cite book\n | last = Cook\n | first = Richard\n | author-link = \n | year = 2005\n | title = Richard Cook's Jazz Encyclopedia\n | publisher = Penguin Books\n | location = London\n | isbn = 0-141-00646-3\n | pages = 9\n}}</ref> He also performs on [[flute]], [[oboe]], [[piccolo]], and [[EWI (musical instrument)|EVI]] (an electronic valve instrument made by Steiner, Crumar company).\n\nAllen is best known for his work with [[Sun Ra]], having recorded and performed mostly in this context since the late 1950s, and having led Sun Ra's Arkestra since 1993. Critic Jason Ankeny<ref>Jason Ankeny,\n [http://www.allmusic.com/artist/marshall-allen-mn0000299353 \"Marshall Allen biography\"], Allmusic.</ref> describes Marshall as \"one of the most distinctive and original saxophonists of the postwar era.\"\n\n==Biography==\nMarshall Allen was born in [[Louisville, Kentucky]].\n\nDuring the [[Second World War]] he enlisted in the [[92nd Infantry Division (United States)|92nd Infantry Division]] and was stationed in France.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.elrarecords.com/ma.html |title=Marshall Allen |accessdate=2007-10-06}}</ref> Allen studied alto saxophone in Paris and played in Europe with [[Art Simmons]] and [[James Moody (saxophonist)|James Moody]].\n\nHe is best known for his mastery of pyrotechnic effects on the alto \u2013 he has said that he \"wanted to play on a broader sound basis rather than on chords\" (1971 interview with [[Tam Fiofori]])<ref>Cited in {{cite book | author=Wilmer, Val |authorlink=Val Wilmer|title=As Serious as Your Life | publisher=Quartet | year=1977 | isbn=0-7043-3164-0}}</ref>). The opportunity came through his long association with [[Sun Ra]], with whom he performed almost exclusively from 1958 to Ra's death in 1993, although he did record outside the Arkestra, with [[Paul Bley]]'s group in 1964 and [[Babatunde Olatunji|Olatunji]]'s group during the mid-1960s. Critic [[Scott Yanow]] has described Allen's playing as \"[[Johnny Hodges]] from another dimension\".\n\nSince Sun Ra and [[John Gilmore (musician)|John Gilmore]] died, Allen has led the Arkestra, and has recorded two albums as their bandleader. In May 2004, Allen celebrated his 80th birthday on stage with the Arkestra, as part of their performance at the Ninth [[Vision Festival]] in New York City. Allen gave other performances on his birthday in 2008 at Sullivan Hall and at [[Iridium Jazz Club]] in 2018, both in New York City.\n\nAllen often appears in NYC-area collaborations with bassist [[Henry Grimes]] and has also participated in the \"Innerzone Orchestra\" together with Francisco Mora Catlett, [[Carl Craig]] and others in an appreciation of Sun Ra's music.\n\n==Discography==\n[[File:Cinema Soloriens @ Band On The Wall, Manchester 4-4-2013 (8620542659).jpg|thumb|200px|Marshall Allen performing with James Harrar's Cinema Soloriens at Band On The Wall, Manchester, 4 April 2013]]\n\nFor Recordings With Sun Ra See: [[Sun Ra]]\n\n===As leader===\n*1988: ''Mark-N-Marshall: Monday''\n*1988: ''Mark-N-Marshall: Tuesday''\n*1999: ''Pozest''\n\n===As co-leader===\n*2010: ''[http://web.roguart.com/shop/album/id/42 Night Logic]'' [https://web.archive.org/web/20111214133349/http://web.roguart.com/main RogueArt]\n\n===As sideman===\n;With [[Paul Bley]]\n*''[[Barrage (Paul Bley album)|Barrage]]'' (ESP-Disk, 1965)\n\n'''With''' [[Terry Adams (musician)|'''Terry Adams''']]\n* ''Terrible'' (New World Records, 1995) \n\n;With [[Trey Anastasio]]\n*\"[[Surrender to the Air]]\" (Elektra, 1996)\n\n;With [[Medeski, Martin and Wood]]\n*''[[The Dropper]]'' (Blue Note, 2000)\n\n;With [[The Muffins]] and [[Knoel Scott]]\n*''Loveletter #2 The Ra Sessions'' (Hobart Films & Records, 2005)\n\n;With Hawk Tubley & The Airtight Chiefs\n*''Cooking With Dynamite!'' (2011)\n\n;With [[Dave Soldier]]\n*''The Eighth Hour of Amduat'' (Mulatta Records, 2016)\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n<!-- * [http://www.l-m-c.org.uk/texts/allen.html An interview with Marshall Allen] not found now -->\n* [http://www.thesunraarkestra.com Official website of the Sun Ra Arkestra under the direction of Marshall Allen]\n* {{Discogs artist|Marshall Allen}}\n\n{{Sun Ra}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Allen, Marshall}}\n[[Category:African-American musicians]]\n[[Category:Free jazz saxophonists]]\n[[Category:Free jazz flautists]]\n[[Category:American jazz alto saxophonists]]\n[[Category:American male saxophonists]]\n[[Category:American jazz flautists]]\n[[Category:American jazz oboists]]\n[[Category:Male jazz musicians]]\n[[Category:Male oboists]]\n[[Category:1924 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Sun Ra Arkestra members]]\n[[Category:Avant-garde jazz flautists]]\n[[Category:Avant-garde jazz saxophonists]]\n[[Category:Military personnel from Louisville, Kentucky]]\n[[Category:Musicians from Louisville, Kentucky]]\n[[Category:American military personnel of World War II]]\n[[Category:Jazz musicians from Kentucky]]\n[[Category:21st-century saxophonists]]\n[[Category:Surrender to the Air members]]\n", "text_old": "{{for|the American journalist|Marshall Allen (journalist)}}\n{{Infobox musical artist <!-- See Wikipedia:WikiProject Musicians -->\n| name                = Marshall Allen\n| image                 = Marshall Allen.jpg\n| caption            = Photo of Marshall Allen by Seth Tisue\n| image_size            = \n| background          = non_vocal_instrumentalist\n| birth_name          = Marshall Allen\n| alias               = \n| birth_date                = {{Birth date and age|1924|5|25}} \n| death_date                = \n| origin              = [[Louisville, Kentucky]], United States\n| instrument          = [[Saxophone]], [[flute]], [[oboe]], [[piccolo]], [[EWI (musical instrument)|EVI]]\n| genre               = [[Jazz]]\n| occupation          = \n| years_active        = \n| label               = \n| associated_acts     = [[Sun Ra]], [[Paul Bley]]\n| website                 = \n| current_members     = \n| past_members        = \n}}\n'''Marshall Belford Allen''' (born May 25, 1924) is an American [[free jazz]] and [[avant-garde jazz]] [[alto saxophone]] player.<ref name=\"RCJE\">{{Cite book\n | last = Cook\n | first = Richard\n | author-link = \n | year = 2005\n | title = Richard Cook's Jazz Encyclopedia\n | publisher = Penguin Books\n | location = London\n | isbn = 0-141-00646-3\n | pages = 9\n}}</ref> He also performs on [[flute]], [[oboe]], [[piccolo]], and [[EWI (musical instrument)|EVI]] (an electronic valve instrument made by Steiner, Crumar company).\n\nAllen is best known for his work with [[Sun Ra]], having recorded and performed mostly in this context since the late 1950s, and having led Sun Ra's Arkestra since 1993. Critic Jason Ankeny<ref>Jason Ankeny,\n [http://www.allmusic.com/artist/marshall-allen-mn0000299353 \"Marshall Allen biography\"], Allmusic.</ref> describes Marshall as \"one of the most distinctive and original saxophonists of the postwar era.\"\n\n==Biography==\nMarshall Allen was born in [[Louisville, Kentucky]].\n\nDuring the [[Second World War]] he enlisted in the [[92nd Infantry Division (United States)|92nd Infantry Division]] and was stationed in France.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.elrarecords.com/ma.html |title=Marshall Allen |accessdate=2007-10-06}}</ref> Allen studied alto saxophone in Paris and played in Europe with [[Art Simmons]] and [[James Moody (saxophonist)|James Moody]].\n\nHe is best known for his mastery of pyrotechnic effects on the alto \u2013 he has said that he \"wanted to play on a broader sound basis rather than on chords\" (1971 interview with [[Tam Fiofori]])<ref>Cited in {{cite book | author=Wilmer, Val |authorlink=Val Wilmer|title=As Serious as Your Life | publisher=Quartet | year=1977 | isbn=0-7043-3164-0}}</ref>). The opportunity came through his long association with [[Sun Ra]], with whom he performed almost exclusively from 1958 to Ra's death in 1993, although he did record outside the Arkestra, with [[Paul Bley]]'s group in 1964 and [[Babatunde Olatunji|Olatunji]]'s group during the mid-1960s. Critic [[Scott Yanow]] has described Allen's playing as \"[[Johnny Hodges]] from another dimension\".\n\nSince Sun Ra and [[John Gilmore (musician)|John Gilmore]] died, Allen has led the Arkestra, and has recorded two albums as their bandleader. In May 2004, Allen celebrated his 80th birthday on stage with the Arkestra, as part of their performance at the Ninth [[Vision Festival]] in New York City. Allen gave other performances on his birthday in 2008 at Sullivan Hall and at [[Iridium Jazz Club]] in 2018, both in New York City.\n\nAllen often appears in NYC-area collaborations with bassist [[Henry Grimes]] and has also participated in the \"Innerzone Orchestra\" together with Francisco Mora Catlett, [[Carl Craig]] and others in an appreciation of Sun Ra's music.\n\n==Discography==\n[[File:Cinema Soloriens @ Band On The Wall, Manchester 4-4-2013 (8620542659).jpg|thumb|200px|Marshall Allen performing with James Harrar's Cinema Soloriens at Band On The Wall, Manchester, 4 April 2013]]\n\nFor Recordings With Sun Ra See: [[Sun Ra]]\n\n===As leader===\n*1988: ''Mark-N-Marshall: Monday''\n*1988: ''Mark-N-Marshall: Tuesday''\n*1999: ''Pozest''\n\n===As co-leader===\n*2010: ''[http://web.roguart.com/shop/album/id/42 Night Logic]'' [https://web.archive.org/web/20111214133349/http://web.roguart.com/main RogueArt]\n\n===As sideman===\n;With [[Paul Bley]]\n*''[[Barrage (Paul Bley album)|Barrage]]'' (ESP-Disk, 1965)\n\n\n'''With''' [[Terry Adams (musician)|'''Terry Adams''']]\n\n* ''Terrible'' (New World Records, 1995) \n\n;With [[Trey Anastasio]]\n*\"[[Surrender to the Air]]\" (Elektra, 1996)\n\n;With [[Medeski, Martin and Wood]]\n*''[[The Dropper]]'' (Blue Note, 2000)\n\n;With [[The Muffins]] and [[Knoel Scott]]\n*''Loveletter #2 The Ra Sessions'' (Hobart Films & Records, 2005)\n\n;With Hawk Tubley & The Airtight Chiefs\n*''Cooking With Dynamite!'' (2011)\n\n;With [[Dave Soldier]]\n*''The Eighth Hour of Amduat'' (Mulatta Records, 2016)\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n<!-- * [http://www.l-m-c.org.uk/texts/allen.html An interview with Marshall Allen] not found now -->\n* [http://www.thesunraarkestra.com Official website of the Sun Ra Arkestra under the direction of Marshall Allen]\n* {{Discogs artist|Marshall Allen}}\n\n{{Sun Ra}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Allen, Marshall}}\n[[Category:African-American musicians]]\n[[Category:Free jazz saxophonists]]\n[[Category:Free jazz flautists]]\n[[Category:American jazz alto saxophonists]]\n[[Category:American male saxophonists]]\n[[Category:American jazz flautists]]\n[[Category:American jazz oboists]]\n[[Category:Male jazz musicians]]\n[[Category:Male oboists]]\n[[Category:1924 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Sun Ra Arkestra members]]\n[[Category:Avant-garde jazz flautists]]\n[[Category:Avant-garde jazz saxophonists]]\n[[Category:Military personnel from Louisville, Kentucky]]\n[[Category:Musicians from Louisville, Kentucky]]\n[[Category:American military personnel of World War II]]\n[[Category:Jazz musicians from Kentucky]]\n[[Category:21st-century saxophonists]]\n[[Category:Surrender to the Air members]]\n", "name_user": "Dgh2125", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eDiscography:formatting", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Marshall_Allen"}
{"title_page": "The Darkness II", "text_new": "{{short description|2012 first-person shooter game}}\n{{Infobox video game\n| title      = The Darkness II\n| image      = The Darkness II cover.jpg\n| caption    = Cover art featuring protagonist Jackie Estacado \n| developer  = [[Digital Extremes]]\n| publisher  = [[2K Games]]\n| director   = Sheldon Carter\n| producer   = Dave Kudirka\n| designer   = Tom Galt\n| programmer = Glen Miner<br/>Darryl Baldock\n| artist     = Mat Tremblay\n| writer     = [[Paul Jenkins (writer)|Paul Jenkins]]\n| composer   = [[Tim Wynn]]\n| series     = ''[[The Darkness (comics)|The Darkness]]''\n| engine     = \n| platforms  = [[Microsoft Windows]]<br/>[[PlayStation 3]]<br/>[[Xbox 360]]<br/>[[macOS|Mac OS X]]\n| released   = {{Video game release|NA|February 7, 2012|PAL|February 10, 2012}}'''OS X'''<br/>{{Video game release|WW|April 18, 2012}}\n| genre      = [[First-person shooter]] <!--psychological horror *isn't* a video game genre-->\n| modes      = [[Single-player video game|Single-player]], [[Multiplayer video game|multiplayer]]\n}}\n\n'''''The Darkness II''''' is a 2012 [[first-person shooter]] video game developed by [[Digital Extremes]] and published by [[2K Games]]. The game is the sequel to ''[[The Darkness (video game)|The Darkness]]'' (2007) and based on the [[The Darkness (comics)|comic book series]] published by [[Top Cow Productions]]. The player controls Jackie Estacado, a mafia hitman who possesses a mysterious power called \"the Darkness\" that grants him supernatural abilities and a pair of Demon Arms.<ref name=\"violence origin\">{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/technology/gamesblog/2012/feb/07/the-darkness-ii-game-review|title=The Darkness II \u2013 review|last=Cowen|first=Nick|date=February 7, 2012|work=[[The Guardian]]|accessdate=March 7, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191005062917/https://www.theguardian.com/technology/gamesblog/2012/feb/07/the-darkness-ii-game-review|archive-date=October 5, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> The game features elements found in [[role-playing video game]]s such as [[skill tree]]s, [[experience (gaming)|experience]], and a four-player cooperative mode. The player must rescue the soul of Jackie's dead girlfriend, which was trapped by the Darkness in hell, and confront the Brotherhood, a group of armed cultists trying to take the Darkness away from Jackie.\n\nDigital Extremes replaced the first game's developer [[Starbreeze Studios]], though [[Paul Jenkins (writer)|Paul Jenkins]] returned to write the script for the sequel. While the main narrative was envisioned to be a personal journey for Jackie, developers described the cooperative multiplayer mode as a \"dark comedy\". Singer [[Mike Patton]] returned to voice the Darkness, and [[Brian Bloom]] provided the voice for Jackie Estacado, replacing [[Kirk Acevedo]]. The development artists hand-painted the majority of the game's assets to create a comic book-influenced visual style.\n\nAnnounced in May 2011, the game was released for [[Microsoft Windows|Windows]], [[PlayStation 3]], and [[Xbox 360]] in February 2012. The game received positive reviews upon release, with critics praising the gameplay, story, pacing, and art style. Criticisms were directed at the game's short length, technical issues, and lack of replay value. The game debuted as the third best-selling game in its first week of release in the United Kingdom.\n\n==Gameplay==\n[[File:The Darkness II gameplay screenshot.jpg|thumb|left|Players can [[dual wield]] weapons and control a pair of Demon Arms. The left arm is used to grab objects while the right arm is used to slash enemies.<ref name=\"EuroGRev\"/>]]\nJackie can use various firearms, such as submachine guns, shotguns, and assault rifles, and has the ability to [[dual wield]] some of these weapons.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.gamesradar.com/darkness-iis-weapons-designer-talks-moody-firearms/|title=The Darkness II's weapons designer talks moody firearms|first=Andrew|last=Hayward|work=[[GamesRadar]]|date=January 12, 2012|accessdate=March 7, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200229153557/https://www.gamesradar.com/darkness-iis-weapons-designer-talks-moody-firearms/|archive-date=February 29, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> Additionally, he is armed with a pair of demon tentacles, which can be used to slash enemies or pick up various items within the environment (parking meters, car doors, etc.) to use as projectile weapons or shields.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.videogamer.com/previews/the-darkness-ii-preview|title=The Darkness II Preview|first=Jamin|last=Smith|work=VideoGamer.com|date=October 13, 2011|accessdate=March 7, 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"EuroGRev\"/> The demon tendrils can rip out the heart of fallen enemies and devour them for [[health (gaming)|health]], pick up enemies for execution, or throw them.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.pcgamer.com/the-monstrous-limbs-of-the-darkness-2/|title=The monstrous limbs of The Darkness 2|first=Tom|last=Senior|work=[[PC Gamer]]|date=July 22, 2015|accessdate=March 7, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180126024052/http://www.pcgamer.com/the-monstrous-limbs-of-the-darkness-2/|archive-date=January 26, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> The player is guided by a Darkling, a goblin-like creature that assists in combat and gathers weapons and ammo.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://venturebeat.com/2011/03/05/gdc-2011-the-darkness-2s-darkling-is-a-crude-companion/|title=GDC 2011: The Darkness 2\u2019s Darkling is a crude companion|date=March 5, 2011|work=[[VentureBeat]]|accessdate=March 7, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161018232102/http://venturebeat.com/2011/03/05/gdc-2011-the-darkness-2s-darkling-is-a-crude-companion/|archive-date=October 18, 2016|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.gamespot.com/articles/the-darkness-ii-qanda-demonic-power/1100-6337614/|title=The Darkness II Q&A - Demonic Power|work=[[GameSpot]]|date=September 30, 2011|accessdate=March 7, 2020}}</ref> At several points, the player can directly control the Darkling, allowing them to squeeze into tight spaces that Jackie cannot enter and execute enemies from behind.<ref>{{cite web|url= https://www.gamesradar.com/darkness-ii-hands-preview-reveals-new-powers-controllable-darkling-and-jenny/|title=The Darkness II hands-on preview reveals new powers, controllable Darkling and Jenny?|first=Mikel|last=Reparaz|work=[[GamesRadar]]|date=October 11, 2011|accessdate=March 7, 2020}}</ref> When exposed to light, Jackie's health regeneration and Darkness abilities are disabled and the Darkling will vanish, leaving Jackie with firearms as his only defense.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://xbox360.gamespy.com/xbox-360/the-darkness-2/1157275p1.html|title=The Interrogation Room: The Darkness II|first=Nathna|last=Meunier|work=[[GameSpy]]|date=March 23, 2011|accessdate=March 7, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160412051245/http://xbox360.gamespy.com/xbox-360/the-darkness-2/1157275p1.html|archive-date=April 12, 2016|url-status=live}}</ref> Jackie's vision will blur and he will experience a high-pitched ringing.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.gamespot.com/articles/the-darkness-ii-exclusive-preview-first-look/1100-6301032/|title=The Darkness II Exclusive Preview - First Look|first=Maxwell|last=McGee|work=[[GameSpot]]|date=February 25, 2011|accessdate=March 7, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150106224636/http://www.gamespot.com/articles/the-darkness-ii-exclusive-preview-first-look/1100-6301032/|archive-date=January 6, 2015|url-status=live}}</ref> The player must avoid directly exposing Jackie to light sources or disable them by shooting out lights or destroying power generators.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.rockpapershotgun.com/2012/02/09/wot-i-think-the-darkness-ii/|title=Wot I Think: The Darkness II|first=John|last=Walker|work=[[Rock, Paper, Shotgun]]|date=February 9, 2012|accessdate=March 7, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190727210143/https://www.rockpapershotgun.com/2012/02/09/wot-i-think-the-darkness-ii/|archive-date=July 27, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nThe game features elements found in [[role-playing video game]]s. Killing enemies, devouring hearts and performing executions earn the player Essence, which can be used to purchase upgrades at various talent shrines. Collecting relics, which serves as [[collectible]]s, earn a small amount of Essence.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.gamesradar.com/darkness-2-relic-locations-guide/|title=The Darkness 2 Relic locations guide|first=Jeff|last=McAllister|work=[[GamesRadar]]|date=February 13, 2012|accessdate=March 7, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190123143708/https://www.gamesradar.com/darkness-2-relic-locations-guide/|archive-date=January 23, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> The [[skill tree]] is divided into four main aspects: Hitman, Execution, Darkness Powers, and Demon Arm.<ref name=\"DestructPre\">{{cite web|url=https://www.destructoid.com/you-should-be-paying-attention-to-the-darkness-ii-213431.phtml/|title=You should be paying attention to The Darkness II|first=Tara|last=Long|work=[[Destructoid]]|date=October 11, 2011|accessdate=March 7, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191028083452/https://www.destructoid.com/you-should-be-paying-attention-to-the-darkness-ii-213431.phtml|archive-date=October 28, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> The Hitman aspect consists of passive upgrades that improve the weapon's reload time and magazine size. The Execution tree allows each execution to net more benefits, such as gaining a massive amount of health, ammo or a shield.<ref name=\"DestructPre\"/> Darkness Powers and the Demon Arms grant players access to active abilities, some of which have a brief [[cooldown]] after use.<ref name=\"GRadarPre\"/><ref name=\"DestructPre\"/> These abilities include Gun Channeling, an ability that gives the player unlimited ammo and enhanced damage for a short time;<ref name=\"DestructPre\"/> Swarm, which distracts enemies; and Black Hole, which triggers a large [[area of effect]] attack that sucks enemies into a vortex.<ref name=\"GRadarPre\">{{cite web|url=https://www.gamesradar.com/darkness-ii-updated-hands-preview/|title=The Darkness II - updated hands-on preview|first=Brett|last=Elston|work=[[GamesRadar]]|date=August 28, 2011|accessdate=March 7, 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe game features a [[cooperative gameplay|cooperative multiplayer]] campaign called ''Vendettas'' that runs parallel to the main campaign and allows up to four players to play together.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.engadget.com/2011/12/06/the-darkness-2-gets-4-player-co-op-mode-in-vendettas-we-count/|title=The Darkness 2 gets 4-player co-op mode in 'Vendettas,' we count the wieldings [update: video, more screens!]|first= Christopher|last=Grant|work=[[Engadget]]|date=June 12, 2011|accessdate=March 7, 2020}}</ref> The story involves four hitmen working for Jackie as they attempt to stop the Brotherhood from obtaining the [[Spear of Destiny]]. Each character has different Darkness powers and is armed with a unique special weapon. For instance, Inugami is a character who uses a Darkness-infused samurai sword, while Shoshanna uses a blunderbuss which can shoot without bullets. Although the mode can be played solo, the experience is significantly more difficult.<ref name=\"WSPOSTcoop\">{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/business/technology/darkness-ii-announces-vendettas-co-op-mode/2011/12/06/gIQAKcUeaO_story.html|title=\u2018Darkness II\u2019 announces \u2018Vendettas\u2019 co-op mode|first=Hayley|last=Tsukayama|work=[[Washington Post]]|date=December 6, 2011|accessdate=March 7, 2020}}</ref> There is an [[arcade game|arcade]] mode called \"Hit List\" that allows players to replay certain ''Vendetta'' missions and complete challenges.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.digitalspy.com/videogames/previews/a354625/the-darkness-ii-vendettas-co-op-multiplayer-preview/|title='The Darkness II' Vendettas co-op multiplayer preview|first=Andrew|last=Laughin|work=[[Digital Spy]]|date=June 12, 2011|accessdate=March 7, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200229155657/https://www.digitalspy.com/videogames/previews/a354625/the-darkness-ii-vendettas-co-op-multiplayer-preview/|archive-date=February 29, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n==Plot==\n{{multiple image|caption_align=center|header_align=center\n | align = right\n | total_width = 320\n\n | image1 = Mike Patton with Fant\u00f4mas Quart Festival Norway 2005.jpg\n | width1 = 500 | height1 = 580\n | caption1 = [[Mike Patton]] voices the Darkness\n\n | image2 = Brian Bloom.jpg\n | width2 = 500 | height2 = 580\n | caption2 = [[Brian Bloom]] voices Jackie Estacado\n}}\n\nThe game begins two years after the events of the first game, with the player controlling Jackie Estacado ([[Brian Bloom]]), who has become head of the Franchetti family and has learned to suppress the&nbsp;Darkness ([[Mike&nbsp;Patton]]), an ancient demonic force which has inhabited Jackie's bloodline for generations. Jackie is haunted by the memory of his murdered girlfriend, Jenny Romano (Stephanie Frame), and sees apparitions of her. While relaxing at a restaurant, Jackie and his crew are attacked by a rival gang. Grievously wounded, Jackie is forced to let the Darkness out once more, restoring his powers. Aided by the Darkling (Peter Newman)\u2014a goblin-like familiar of the Darkness\u2014Jackie pursues his attackers into the subway. Jackie is mesmerized by a vision of Jenny on the tracks, only to be apparently hit by a train. He wakes up in what appears to be an asylum occupied by his crew.\n\nReawakening back into the living world, Jackie regroups with his men at his penthouse to plan a counterattack. One of Jackie's closest associates, Jimmy the Grape ([[Frank Ashmore]]), provides a lead that points to Swifty, a smaller crime boss. After subduing Swifty, he explains that a shady group he met at the Brimstone Club brothel paid him to put the hit on Jackie. Before he can reveal anything else, the Darkness brutally murders him. Vinnie ([[Rick Pasqualone]])\u2014one of Jackie's men\u2014enlists his contact at Brimstone to help them. At the club, Jackie encounters armed cultists of the Brotherhood, a secret society who ordered the hit and wish to use the Darkness for themselves. They ambush Jackie with blinding lights that inhibit the Darkness\u2019 powers, and Jackie is knocked out. Waking up, he finds himself crucified and a device (the Siphon) draining his dark power. He is greeted by Victor ([[William Salyers]]) who offers to take the Darkness from him in exchange for the lives of his family. Refusing, he loses consciousness momentarily and finds himself in Hell where the Darkness keeps Jenny's soul.\n\nAfter Jackie breaks free, Victor threatens to murder Jackie's Aunt, Sarah (Bridger Fox). As the club burns, the Darkness offers Jenny's soul in exchange for the Siphon. Jackie regroups with his men to retake the penthouse, but Jackie is shot and incapacitated by Bragg, a top Brotherhood enforcer, who murders Sarah. After being shot, Jackie awakens in a psychiatric ward where Jenny and members of his crew appear as staff and patients. They tell him that his mob stories are delusions. At Sarah's funeral, the Brotherhood launches another attack. Jackie subdues Bragg, who reveals that Victor is operating out of an abandoned theme park. Jackie is soon captured by Victor in an [[Iron maiden (torture device)|iron maiden]] and loses consciousness from blood loss. Again, he wakes in the ward, but the janitor, revealed to be his Darkling, explains that the asylum is a trap for Jackie to keep him alive and away from Jenny.\n\nJackie awakens to find that Victor has successfully drained the Darkness from him. The Darkling helps Jackie escape and retake a small portion of the Darkness. Jackie pursues Victor through a mansion once owned by Carlo Estacado, Jackie's father. Jackie learns from Victor that Carlo had promised the Darkness to the Brotherhood to ensure Jackie didn't have to suffer as he did. Reaching the attic, Jackie kills Victor and impales himself with the Siphon, regaining the Darkness and killing himself to rescue Jenny from Hell. Jackie once again wakes up in the psychiatric ward where the staff offer to take him to Jenny. The Darkling appears and sacrifices himself to help Jackie escape. Jackie reaches the roof and is confronted by Victor (appearing as a doctor), Jenny, and an orderly who attempt to convince Jackie that his life as a mob boss is a delusion and that the world in the psychiatric ward is real.\n\nOn the roof of the asylum, the player is given a choice to either have Jackie stay with Jenny in the ward, or reject the asylum and attempt to reach Hell. If the player chooses to stay, both Jenny and Jackie will head back into the asylum and slow dance to \"[[I Only Have Eyes for You]]\", and the game ends. If the player chooses to reject the asylum, Jackie will jump from the roof and fall into Hell. The Darkness, in a fit of rage, sends demons to stop Jackie from reaching Jenny, but Jackie manages to release Jenny from her bindings and the couple embrace. In a post-credits scene, Jenny is revealed to have become the new host for the [[Angelus (comics)|Angelus]], who has seen the destruction Jackie and the Darkness have caused, and states Jackie has become too powerful and leaves them trapped in Hell; leaving an enraged Jackie screaming as the screen fades out.\n\n==Development==\n[[File:Paul Jenkins, 2006.jpg|thumb|right|150px|[[Paul Jenkins (writer)|Paul Jenkins]] returned to write the game.]]\nPublisher [[2K Games]] approached Canadian developer [[Digital Extremes]] to develop ''The Darkness II'', replacing [[Starbreeze Studios]] which worked on the first game. The team worked on the title for three years. The team spent a lot of time creating the game's narrative, with [[Paul Jenkins (writer)|Paul Jenkins]] returning as the title's writer.<ref name=\"TD2 Star\">{{cite web|url=https://www.thestar.com/entertainment/2012/05/24/the_darkness_sequel_shines_light_on_london_video_game_studio.html|title=\u2018The Darkness\u2019 sequel shines light on London video game studio|first=Neil|last=Davidson|work=[[Toronto Star|The Star]]|date=May 24, 2012|accessdate=March 13, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200229153553/https://www.thestar.com/entertainment/2012/05/24/the_darkness_sequel_shines_light_on_london_video_game_studio.html|archive-date=February 29, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> According to Starbreeze's CEO Mikael Nermark, the company was not given the option of working on the sequel and was already busy working on ''[[Syndicate (2012 video game)|Syndicate]]'' when ''The Darkness II'' was announced.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.engadget.com/2011/05/17/starbreeze-giving-the-darkness-2-to-digital-extremes-was-out-of/|title=Starbreeze: Giving The Darkness 2 to Digital Extremes was out of our hands|first=David|last=Hinkle|work=[[Engadget]]|date=May 17, 2011|accessdate=March 13, 2020}}</ref>\n\nAccording to Carter, Digital Extremes agreed to assume development responsibilities as the team wanted to create a shooter with a large emphasis on the story.<ref name=\"TD2 Star\"/><ref name=\"close personal\"/> Both Jenkins and the team at Digital Extremes worked closely, with the team making adjustments to Jenkins' script to suit the gameplay.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.pcgamer.com/darkness-ii-director-talks-narrative-and-design/|title=Darkness II director talks narrative and design|first=Rob|last=Zacny|work=[[PC Gamer]]|date=September 26, 2011|accessdate=March 13, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200229153553/https://www.pcgamer.com/darkness-ii-director-talks-narrative-and-design/|archive-date=February 29, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> Carter called the narrative a \"love story\", which he felt \"[balanced] the adrenaline of the action\",<ref name=\"TD2 Star\"/> while the first part of the game's three-act plot was about \"survival\" since Jackie was attacked by an opposing mob.<ref name=\"GspotInt\">{{cite web|url=https://www.gamespot.com/articles/the-darkness-ii-qanda-demonic-power/1100-6337614/|title=The Darkness II Q&A - Demonic Power|work=[[GameSpot]]|date=September 30, 2011|accessdate=March 13, 2020}}</ref> The team spent a lot of time working on the tone of Jackie. Carter compared Jackie to [[Tony Soprano]], a \"badass\" character who has to face a lot of internal struggles.<ref name=\"close personal\">{{cite web|url=https://www.vg247.com/2011/03/04/death-is-no-option-digital-extremes-on-the-darkness-ii/|title=Death is no option: Digital Extremes on The Darkness II|first=Nathan|last=Grayson|work=[[VG 247]]|date=March 4, 2011|accessdate=March 13, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200229153556/https://www.vg247.com/2011/03/04/death-is-no-option-digital-extremes-on-the-darkness-ii/|archive-date=February 29, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> The team hoped that the story could make the players sympathize with Jackie. According to designer Tom Galt, while Jackie was a mob boss on the surface, \"in his heart he is human and a good-natured guy\".<ref name=\"art\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.siliconera.com/interview-how-shapes-and-tentacles-go-hand-in-hand-in-the-darkness-ii/|title=Interview: How Shapes And Tentacles Go Hand In Hand In The Darkness II|work=Siliconera|date=April 8, 2011|accessdate=March 13, 2020}}</ref> With the game's large focus on narrative, the Darkling was given a personality and played a huge role in the story.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://nypost.com/2011/07/29/the-darkness-ii-more-than-just-gore-but-theres-lots-of-that-as-well/|title=The Darkness II: more than just gore \u2014 but there\u2019s lots of that as well|first=William|last=Vikta|work=[[New York Post]]|date=July 29, 2011|accessdate=March 13, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200229153556/https://nypost.com/2011/07/29/the-darkness-ii-more-than-just-gore-but-theres-lots-of-that-as-well/|archive-date=February 29, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> The game does not cut to [[Third-person (video games)|third-person]] so that a limited extent of control can be granted to players even in cinematics.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.gamasutra.com/view/news/37271/Interview_The_Darkness_IIs_Sheldon_Carter_On_Cinematic_Storytelling.php|title=Interview: The Darkness II's Sheldon Carter On Cinematic Storytelling|first=Frank|last=Cifaldi|work==[[Gamasutra]]|date=September 26, 2011|accessdate=March 13, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200229153605/https://www.gamasutra.com/view/news/37271/Interview_The_Darkness_IIs_Sheldon_Carter_On_Cinematic_Storytelling.php|archive-date=February 29, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> While the game has a heavy narrative focus, all [[cutscene]]s and cinematics can be skipped for players who only want to enjoy the gameplay.<ref name=\"TD2 Star\"/>  One of the biggest requests from players of the first game was to have [[Mike Patton]] return to voice the Darkness.<ref name=\"GspotInt\"/> [[Nolan North]] served as a stand-in voice actor for Jackie during the game's pre-production, before [[Brian Bloom]] was chosen to voice the character.<ref name=\"abc\">{{cite web|url=https://www.abc.net.au/technology/articles/2012/02/13/3429221.htm|title=The Darkness II: from comic to video game and beyond|first=Jenna|last=Pitcher|work=[[Australian Broadcasting Corporation|ABC]]|date=February 13, 2012|accessdate=March 13, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140209133910/http://www.abc.net.au/technology/articles/2012/02/13/3429221.htm|archive-date=February 9, 2014|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n''The Darkness'' comic was a large inspiration for the team. The team read the comic and decided to adopt a comic book-influenced \"graphic noir\" [[art style]], as they believed the comic's use of high contrast colors contributed to its success.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mtv.com/news/2621631/the-darkness-ii-digital-extremes-sheldon-carter-talks-the-hottest-game-of-the-year/|title=The Darkness II: Digital Extremes' Sheldon Carter Talks The Hottest Game of the Year|first=Valarie|last=Gallager|work=[[MTV]]|date=May 13, 2011|accessdate=March 13, 2020}}</ref> The team used some of the assets made by Starbreeze as a reference,<ref name=\"art\"/> and created new ones using their own internal proprietary [[game engine]] named the Evolution Engine, which powered the studio's previous game ''[[Dark Sector]]'' (2008).<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.engadget.com/2011/02/09/the-darkness-2-uses-digital-extremes-evolution-engine/|title=The Darkness 2 uses Digital Extreme's Evolution Engine|first=JC|last=Fletcher|work=[[Engadget]]|date=February 9, 2011|accessdate=March 13, 2020}}</ref> The development artists hand-painted the majority of the game's assets, though this idea was initially met with resistance within the art team due to the huge amount of workload such an approach would create.<ref name=\"abc\"/>\n\nThe team decided to make the title more action-orientated in an attempt to differentiate itself from its predecessor.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.destructoid.com/tara-long-interviews-seth-olshfski-for-the-darkness-2-210037.phtml|title=Tara Long interviews Seth Olshfski for The Darkness 2|first=Victoria|last=Medina|work=[[Destructoid]]|date=August 27, 2011|accessdate=March 13, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150912014901/http://www.destructoid.com/tara-long-interviews-seth-olshfski-for-the-darkness-2-210037.phtml|archive-date=September 12, 2015|url-status=live}}</ref> The shooting mechanic was refined,<ref name=\"close personal\"/> and the concept of \"quad-wielding\", which allows players to engage in combat using both the Demon Arms and duel-wielding weapons, was introduced. Carter explained that they saw the Demon Arms as an opportunity to make the combat more \"up close and personal\".<ref name=\"close personal\"/> The team changed the game's abilities to supplement this, such as turning the ability of Black Hole into a random drop from enemies.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.vg247.com/2011/07/19/the-darkness-ii-limits-black-hole-use-to-drops/|title=The Darkness II limits Black Hole use to drops|first=Brenna|last=Hillier|work=[[VG 247]]|date=July 19, 2011|accessdate=March 13, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161104011415/http://www.vg247.com/2011/07/19/the-darkness-ii-limits-black-hole-use-to-drops/|archive-date=November 4, 2016|url-status=live}}</ref> The quad-wielding mechanic enabled the combat to have more variety, allowing players to approach the same scenario with different combat styles and encourages players to experiment with different tactics. The gameplay was designed to be violent, with some execution animations being removed for being not \"extravagant\" enough.<ref name=\"TD2 Star\"/>  To ensure the game was not too easy, the team disabled Jackie's powers when he is exposed to light and created various enemy types to challenge the player in different ways.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.digitalspy.com/videogames/a361254/the-darkness-ii-interview-bringing-back-a-cult-classic/|title='The Darkness II' interview: Bringing back a cult classic|first=Andrew|last=Laughin|work=[[Digital Spy]]|date=January 20, 2012|accessdate=March 13, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200229153553/https://www.digitalspy.com/videogames/a361254/the-darkness-ii-interview-bringing-back-a-cult-classic/|archive-date=February 29, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nThe game's cooperative mode Vendetta features a story that runs parallel to the game's main narrative. The team envisioned Vendetta as a [[dark comedy]] with over-the-top characters. It is tonally very different from the main game, and the team hoped that players would use the Vendetta mode to \"blow off some steam\" after experiencing Jackie's story in the main narrative. The team used the mode to explore other characters and elements in the universe, and Jenkins has written more than 10 pages of backstory for each of the four playable characters.<ref name=\"WSPOSTcoop\"/>\n\n2K unveiled the game in May 2011.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ign.com/articles/2011/02/08/the-darkness-ii-unveiled|title=The Darkness II Unveiled|first=Martin|last=Robinson|work=[[IGN]]|date=May 9, 2012|accessdate=March 13, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190412221908/https://www.ign.com/articles/2011/02/08/the-darkness-ii-unveiled|archive-date=April 12, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> The game was initially set to be released in October the same year, though 2K announced in July 2011 that the game would be delayed until February 2012.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.gamespot.com/articles/the-darkness-ii-delayed-to-february-7/1100-6324489/|title=The Darkness II delayed to February 7|work=[[GameSpot]]|date=July 19, 2011|accessdate=March 13, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190916115907/https://www.gamespot.com/articles/the-darkness-ii-delayed-to-february-7/1100-6324489/|archive-date=September 16, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> Players who pre-ordered the game would be upgraded to the Limited Edition; which includes gameplay bonuses, illustration drawn by [[Marc Silvestri]], and digital download for ''The Darkness Origins Volume 1'' and ''Volume 2''.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.eurogamer.net/articles/2011-10-05-darkness-2-pre-order-bonus-revealed|title=Darkness 2 pre-order bonus revealed|first=Wesley|last=Yin-Poole|work=[[Eurogamer]]|date=October 5, 2011|accessdate=March 13, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181128102444/https://www.eurogamer.net/articles/2011-10-05-darkness-2-pre-order-bonus-revealed|archive-date=November 28, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> 2K provided extensive marketing for the game, launching a four-week promotion program on [[Kerrang Radio]], partnering with [[Forbidden Planet (bookstore)|Forbidden Planet]] for window displays and in-store promotions, and placing TV advertisements on both [[SyFy]] and [[Horror Channel]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.mcvuk.com/business-news/retail/the-darkness-ii-ad-plan-revealed/|title=The Darkness II ad plan revealed|work=MCVUK|date=February 8, 2012|accessdate=March 13, 2020}}</ref> A [[demoscene|demo]] for the game was released in January 2012 on [[Steam (software)|Steam]], [[Xbox Live Arcade]] and [[PlayStation Network]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.destructoid.com/the-darkness-ii-finally-has-a-demo-on-the-way-219507.phtml|title=The Darkness II finally has a demo on the way|first=Brett|last=Zeidler|work=[[Destructoid]]|date=January 11, 2011|accessdate=March 17, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150906085836/http://www.destructoid.com/the-darkness-ii-finally-has-a-demo-on-the-way-219507.phtml|archive-date=September 6, 2015|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n==Reception==\n===Critical reception===\n{{video game reviews\n| MC = (PC) 77/100<ref name=\"MCPC\">{{cite web |url=http://www.metacritic.com/game/pc/the-darkness-ii |title=The Darkness II for PC Reviews |website=[[Metacritic]] |accessdate=March 20, 2012 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120314222837/http://www.metacritic.com/game/pc/the-darkness-ii |archive-date=March 14, 2012 |url-status=live }}</ref><br/>(PS3) 79/100<ref name=\"MCPS3\">{{cite web |url=http://www.metacritic.com/game/playstation-3/the-darkness-ii |title=The Darkness II for PlayStation 3 Reviews |website=Metacritic |accessdate=March 20, 2012 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120320234559/http://www.metacritic.com/game/playstation-3/the-darkness-ii |archive-date=March 20, 2012 |url-status=live }}</ref><br/>(X360) 80/100<ref name=\"MCX360\">{{cite web |url=http://www.metacritic.com/game/xbox-360/the-darkness-ii |title=The Darkness II for Xbox 360 Reviews |website=Metacritic |accessdate=March 20, 2012 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120228191020/http://www.metacritic.com/game/xbox-360/the-darkness-ii |archive-date=February 28, 2012 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n| Destruct = 7.5/10<ref name=\"DestructRev\">{{cite web|url=https://www.destructoid.com/review-the-darkness-ii-221168.phtml|title=Review: The Darkness II|first=Conrad|last=Zimmerman|work=[[Destructoid]]|date=February 7, 2012|accessdate=March 13, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190502153823/https://www.destructoid.com/review-the-darkness-ii-221168.phtml|archive-date=May 2, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n| GI = 7/10<ref name=\"GIRev\">{{cite web|url=https://www.gameinformer.com/games/the_darkness_ii/b/xbox360/archive/2012/02/07/a-lovesick-killer-loses-his-soul.aspx|title=The Darkness II Review: A Lovesick Killer Loses His Soul|first=Andrew|last=Reiner|work=[[Game Informer]]|date=February 7, 2012|accessdate=March 13, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190824155221/https://www.gameinformer.com/games/the_darkness_ii/b/xbox360/archive/2012/02/07/a-lovesick-killer-loses-his-soul.aspx|archive-date=August 24, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n| EuroG = 7/10<ref name=\"EuroGRev\">{{cite web|url=https://www.eurogamer.net/articles/2012-02-07-the-darkness-2-review|title=The Darkness 2 Review|first=Dan|last=Whitehead|work=[[Eurogamer]]|date=February 7, 2012|accessdate=March 13, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191005062917/https://www.eurogamer.net/articles/2012-02-07-the-darkness-2-review|archive-date=October 5, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n| GRadar = {{Rating|4|5}}<ref name=\"GRadarRev\">{{cite web|url=https://www.gamesradar.com/the-darkness-ii-review/|title=The Darkness II review|first=Mikel|last=Reparaz|work=[[GamesRadar]]|date=February 7, 2012|accessdate=March 13, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191005062926/https://www.gamesradar.com/the-darkness-ii-review/|archive-date=October 5, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n| GSpot = 7/10<ref name=\"GspotRev\">{{cite web|url=https://www.gamespot.com/reviews/the-darkness-ii-review/1900-6349843|title=The Darkness II review|first=Kevin|last=VanOrd|work=[[GameSpot]]|date=February 7, 2012|accessdate=March 13, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180331095104/https://www.gamespot.com/reviews/the-darkness-ii-review/1900-6349843/|archive-date=March 31, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>\n| GameRev ={{Rating|4|5}}<ref name=\"GameRev\">{{cite web |last=Bischoff |first=Daniel R. |url=https://www.gamerevolution.com/review/54289-the-darkness-ii-xbox360-review |title=The Darkness II Review (X360) |work=[[Game Revolution]] |date=February 7, 2012 |accessdate=July 13, 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190502153829/https://www.gamerevolution.com/review/54289-the-darkness-ii-xbox360-review |archive-date=May 2, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n| IGN = 8/10<ref name=\"IGNRev\">{{cite web|url=https://www.ign.com/articles/2012/02/07/the-darkness-ii-review|title=The Darkness II review|first=Anthony|last=Gallegos|work=[[IGN]]|date=February 8, 2012|accessdate=March 13, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190515115935/https://www.ign.com/articles/2012/02/07/the-darkness-ii-review|archive-date=May 15, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n| Joystiq = {{Rating|4|5}}<ref name=\"JoystiqRev\">{{cite web|url=https://www.engadget.com/2012/02/20/the-darkness-2-review/|title=The Darkness 2 review: Shooting bullets off a list|first=Ben|last=Gilbert|work=[[Engadget]]|date=February 20, 2012|accessdate=March 13, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160531004712/http://www.engadget.com/2012/02/20/the-darkness-2-review/|archive-date=May 31, 2016|url-status=live}}</ref>\n| PCGUS = 80/100<ref name=\"PCGUSRev\">{{cite web|url=https://www.pcgamer.com/the-darkness-2-review/|title=The Darkness 2 review|first=Rich|last=McCormick|work=[[PC Gamer]]|date=February 7, 2012|accessdate=March 13, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191005062916/https://www.pcgamer.com/the-darkness-2-review/|archive-date=October 5, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n}}\n\nThe story received critical acclaim from players. Mikel Reparaz from [[GamesRadar]] described the narrative as \"part mob drama, part surreal comedy, and part supernatural revenge romance\", though he disliked the [[cliffhanger]] ending. While the game focuses on the relationship between Jackie and Jenny, Reparaz noted that the supporting characters were \"endearing\", and remarked that they were well-written and well-acted. He stated he liked the combinations of gun-play and Demon Arms gameplay, which he felt turned Jackie into \"an unstoppable dynamo of horror\". He also enjoyed the execution animations, which he felt were \"brutal\" and \"never quite get old\", though he felt that the gun-play became repetitive by the end of the game.<ref name=\"GRadarRev\"/> Anthony Gallegos from ''[[IGN]]'' felt that the story was not as immediately interesting as the first game and noted that it reused some of its predecessors' plot devices. However, he remarked that some of the scenes with Jenny were \"touching\", which made the story more \"personal\" for the player. He further commented that the game's story focus enabled the title to have better pacing.<ref name=\"IGNRev\"/> Rich McCormick from ''[[PC Gamer]]'' praised the story for being \"involving\", and that the title \"plays with concepts of [[unreliable narrator|unreliable narration]] in a way that only games allow\".<ref name=\"PCGUSRev\"/> Conrad Zimmerman from ''[[Destructoid]]'' felt the narrative was fairly average, but the game's storytelling was \"handled remarkably well\".<ref name=\"DestructRev\"/> Andrew Reiner from ''[[Game Informer]]'' remarked that unlike the original game, the title is more of a fast-paced shooter than a supernatural thriller, and he felt that the story and the characters were inferior when compared to the first game.<ref name=\"GIRev\"/> Kevin VanOrd from ''[[GameSpot]]'' praised the character development and the game's pacing. He described the story as \"unusual\" and \"creepy\", and added that the game's narrative excels when it \"plays with your expectations and has you wondering\".<ref name=\"GspotRev\"/>\n\nThe gameplay received a positive response from critics. Daniel Bischoff from ''[[Game Revolution]]'' called the gun-play \"responsive\" and the Demon Arms \"fun to control\". He particularly liked the combat variety and enemy types, which put the players in various combat scenarios. However, he was disappointed by the game's length, which lasted for only seven hours.<ref name=\"GameRev\"/> Zimmerman agreed that the game was short, but said the title was fun throughout.<ref name=\"GRadarRev\"/> Dan Whitehead from ''[[Eurogamer]]'' also praised the Demon Arms and added that it helped \"opening up combat possibilities that other shooters can't hope to compete with\". He further praised the developer for making the combat faster and refining the gameplay of the original.<ref name=\"EuroGRev\"/> Gallegos praised the combat for being \"vastly superior\" to the first game and said that Jackie's overpowered nature made the game more exciting as players could focus on fun ways to kill enemies. He also liked the skill trees, which he felt have reinvigorated the combat during the later sections of the game.<ref name=\"IGNRev\"/> McCormick noted that the game's control was not too overwhelming for players despite needing to control multiple limbs at once. However, he was disappointed by the final levels, which he felt was a \"slog\" to play through.<ref name=\"PCGUSRev\"/> Reiner praised the game for making players feel powerful, but he felt that the game was repetitive due to the lack of combat variety and remarked that combat \"relies on reflexes more than strategy\".<ref name=\"GIRev\"/> Most reviewers thought that the cooperative multiplayer mode was fun and that it provided extra gameplay for an otherwise short title,<ref name=\"DestructRev\"/><ref name=\"IGNRev\"/><ref name=\"GRadarRev\"/> though both Ben Gilbert from ''[[Joystiq]]'' and Zimmerman thought the combat not as exciting as the main game since the playable characters in the Vendetta mode do not have Demon Arms.<ref name=\"JoystiqRev\"/><ref name=\"DestructRev\"/> Whitehead noted that the mode was \"basic to the point of being crude\", though he felt the secondary story was \"enjoyable\".<ref name=\"EuroGRev\"/>\n\nThe game's presentation received mixed reviews. Gilbert praised the art direction, calling it \"gorgeous\" and \"impressive\".<ref name=\"JoystiqRev\"/> Zimmerman liked the cel-shaded graphics, which he felt was \"evocative of the comic books from which these games originate\" and made the game \"surprisingly easy to get sucked in\". Reiner, however, felt that the new art style did not capture the eerie feeling of the original game.<ref name=\"GIRev\"/> Gallegos noted that the reviewed copy suffered from [[software bugs]], broken animations, [[glitches]], and [[frame rate]] issues and felt that the game was marred by polish issues.<ref name=\"IGNRev\"/>\n\n===Sales===\nThe game was the third best-selling retail game in its week of release in the UK, surpassed by ''[[Kingdoms of Amalur: Reckoning]]'' and ''[[Final Fantasy XIII-2]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.eurogamer.net/articles/2012-02-13-uk-top-40-kingdoms-of-amalur-reckoning-beats-darkness-2|title=UK Top 40: Kingdoms of Amalur: Reckoning beats Darkness 2|first=Tom|last=Phillips|work=[[Eurogamer]]|date=February 13, 2012|accessdate=March 13, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200207090510/https://www.eurogamer.net/articles/2012-02-13-uk-top-40-kingdoms-of-amalur-reckoning-beats-darkness-2|archive-date=February 7, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{Official website|http://www.embracethedarkness.com}}\n* {{moby game|id=/darkness-ii}}\n\n{{Digital Extremes}}\n{{Witchblade}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Darkness Ii, The}}\n[[Category:2012 video games]]\n[[Category:Dark fantasy video games]]\n[[Category:Darkness in fiction]]\n[[Category:First-person shooters]]\n[[Category:MacOS games]]\n[[Category:Multiplayer and single-player video games]]\n[[Category:Organized crime video games]]\n[[Category:PlayStation 3 games]]\n[[Category:Superhero video games]]\n[[Category:Take-Two Interactive games]]\n[[Category:Video games set in New York City]]\n[[Category:Video game sequels]]\n[[Category:Video games based on Top Cow Productions]]\n[[Category:Video games developed in Canada]]\n[[Category:Video games with cel-shaded animation]]\n[[Category:Windows games]]\n[[Category:Xbox 360 games]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|2012 first-person shooter game}}\n{{Infobox video game\n| title      = The Darkness II\n| image      = The Darkness II cover.jpg\n| caption    = Cover art featuring protagonist Jackie Estacado \n| developer  = [[Digital Extremes]]\n| publisher  = [[2K Games]]\n| director   = Sheldon Carter\n| producer   = Dave Kudirka\n| designer   = Tom Galt\n| programmer = Glen Miner<br/>Darryl Baldock\n| artist     = Mat Tremblay\n| writer     = [[Paul Jenkins (writer)|Paul Jenkins]]\n| composer   = [[Tim Wynn]]\n| series     = ''[[The Darkness (comics)|The Darkness]]''\n| engine     = \n| platforms  = [[Microsoft Windows]]<br/>[[PlayStation 3]]<br/>[[Xbox 360]]<br/>[[macOS|Mac OS X]]\n| released   = {{Video game release|NA|February 7, 2012|PAL|February 10, 2012}}'''OS X'''<br/>{{Video game release|WW|April 18, 2012}}\n| genre      = [[First-person shooter]] <!--psychological horror *isn't* a video game genre-->\n| modes      = [[Single-player video game|Single-player]], [[Multiplayer video game|multiplayer]]\n}}\n\n'''''The Darkness II''''' is a 2012 [[first-person shooter]] video game developed by [[Digital Extremes]] and published by [[2K Games]]. The game is the sequel to ''[[The Darkness (video game)|The Darkness]]'' (2007) and based on the [[The Darkness (comics)|comic book series]] published by [[Top Cow Productions]]. The player controls Jackie Estacado, a mafia hitman who possesses a mysterious power called \"the Darkness\" that grants him supernatural abilities and a pair of Demon Arms.<ref name=\"violence origin\">{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/technology/gamesblog/2012/feb/07/the-darkness-ii-game-review|title=The Darkness II \u2013 review|last=Cowen|first=Nick|date=February 7, 2012|work=[[The Guardian]]|accessdate=March 7, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191005062917/https://www.theguardian.com/technology/gamesblog/2012/feb/07/the-darkness-ii-game-review|archive-date=October 5, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> The game features elements found in [[role-playing video game]]s such as [[skill tree]]s, [[experience (gaming)|experience]], and a four-player cooperative mode. The player must rescue the soul of Jackie's dead girlfriend, which was trapped by the Darkness in hell, and confront the Brotherhood, a group of armed cultists trying to take the Darkness away from Jackie.\n\nDigital Extremes replaced the first game's developer [[Starbreeze Studios]], though [[Paul Jenkins (writer)|Paul Jenkins]] returned to write the script for the sequel. While the main narrative was envisioned to be a personal journey for Jackie, developers described the cooperative multiplayer mode as a \"dark comedy\". Singer [[Mike Patton]] returned to voice the Darkness, and [[Brian Bloom]] provided the voice for Jackie Estacado, replacing [[Kirk Acevedo]]. The development artists hand-painted the majority of the game's assets to create a comic book-influenced visual style.\n\nAnnounced in May 2011, the game was released for [[Microsoft Windows|Windows]], [[PlayStation 3]], and [[Xbox 360]] in February 2012. The game received positive reviews upon release, with critics praising the gameplay, story, pacing, and art style. Criticisms were directed at the game's short length, technical issues, and lack of replay value. The game debuted as the third best-selling game in its first week of release in the United Kingdom.\n\n==Gameplay==\n[[File:The Darkness II gameplay screenshot.jpg|thumb|left|Players can [[dual wield]] weapons and control a pair of Demon Arms. The left arm is used to grab objects while the right arm is used to slash enemies.<ref name=\"EuroGRev\"/>]]\nJackie can use various firearms, such as submachine guns, shotguns, and assault rifles, and has the ability to [[dual wield]] some of these weapons.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.gamesradar.com/darkness-iis-weapons-designer-talks-moody-firearms/|title=The Darkness II's weapons designer talks moody firearms|first=Andrew|last=Hayward|work=[[GamesRadar]]|date=January 12, 2012|accessdate=March 7, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200229153557/https://www.gamesradar.com/darkness-iis-weapons-designer-talks-moody-firearms/|archive-date=February 29, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> Additionally, he is armed with a pair of demon tentacles, which can be used to slash enemies or pick up various items within the environment (parking meters, car doors, etc.) to use as projectile weapons or shields.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.videogamer.com/previews/the-darkness-ii-preview|title=The Darkness II Preview|first=Jamin|last=Smith|work=VideoGamer.com|date=October 13, 2011|accessdate=March 7, 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"EuroGRev\"/> The demon tendrils can rip out the heart of fallen enemies and devour them for [[health (gaming)|health]], pick up enemies for execution, or throw them.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.pcgamer.com/the-monstrous-limbs-of-the-darkness-2/|title=The monstrous limbs of The Darkness 2|first=Tom|last=Senior|work=[[PC Gamer]]|date=July 22, 2015|accessdate=March 7, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180126024052/http://www.pcgamer.com/the-monstrous-limbs-of-the-darkness-2/|archive-date=January 26, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> The player is guided by a Darkling, a goblin-like creature that assists in combat and gathers weapons and ammo.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://venturebeat.com/2011/03/05/gdc-2011-the-darkness-2s-darkling-is-a-crude-companion/|title=GDC 2011: The Darkness 2\u2019s Darkling is a crude companion|date=March 5, 2011|work=[[VentureBeat]]|accessdate=March 7, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161018232102/http://venturebeat.com/2011/03/05/gdc-2011-the-darkness-2s-darkling-is-a-crude-companion/|archive-date=October 18, 2016|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.gamespot.com/articles/the-darkness-ii-qanda-demonic-power/1100-6337614/|title=The Darkness II Q&A - Demonic Power|work=[[GameSpot]]|date=September 30, 2011|accessdate=March 7, 2020}}</ref> At several points, the player can directly control the Darkling, allowing them to squeeze into tight spaces that Jackie cannot enter and execute enemies from behind.<ref>{{cite web|url= https://www.gamesradar.com/darkness-ii-hands-preview-reveals-new-powers-controllable-darkling-and-jenny/|title=The Darkness II hands-on preview reveals new powers, controllable Darkling and Jenny?|first=Mikel|last=Reparaz|work=[[GamesRadar]]|date=October 11, 2011|accessdate=March 7, 2020}}</ref> When exposed to light, Jackie's health regeneration and Darkness abilities are disabled and the Darkling will vanish, leaving Jackie with firearms as his only defense.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://xbox360.gamespy.com/xbox-360/the-darkness-2/1157275p1.html|title=The Interrogation Room: The Darkness II|first=Nathna|last=Meunier|work=[[GameSpy]]|date=March 23, 2011|accessdate=March 7, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160412051245/http://xbox360.gamespy.com/xbox-360/the-darkness-2/1157275p1.html|archive-date=April 12, 2016|url-status=live}}</ref> Jackie's vision will blur and he will experience a high-pitched ringing.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.gamespot.com/articles/the-darkness-ii-exclusive-preview-first-look/1100-6301032/|title=The Darkness II Exclusive Preview - First Look|first=Maxwell|last=McGee|work=[[GameSpot]]|date=February 25, 2011|accessdate=March 7, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150106224636/http://www.gamespot.com/articles/the-darkness-ii-exclusive-preview-first-look/1100-6301032/|archive-date=January 6, 2015|url-status=live}}</ref> The player must avoid directly exposing Jackie to light sources or disable them by shooting out lights or destroying power generators.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.rockpapershotgun.com/2012/02/09/wot-i-think-the-darkness-ii/|title=Wot I Think: The Darkness II|first=John|last=Walker|work=[[Rock, Paper, Shotgun]]|date=February 9, 2012|accessdate=March 7, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190727210143/https://www.rockpapershotgun.com/2012/02/09/wot-i-think-the-darkness-ii/|archive-date=July 27, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nThe game features elements found in [[role-playing video game]]s. Killing enemies, devouring hearts and performing executions earn the player Essence, which can be used to purchase upgrades at various talent shrines. Collecting relics, which serves as [[collectible]]s, earn a small amount of Essence.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.gamesradar.com/darkness-2-relic-locations-guide/|title=The Darkness 2 Relic locations guide|first=Jeff|last=McAllister|work=[[GamesRadar]]|date=February 13, 2012|accessdate=March 7, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190123143708/https://www.gamesradar.com/darkness-2-relic-locations-guide/|archive-date=January 23, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> The [[skill tree]] is divided into four main aspects: Hitman, Execution, Darkness Powers, and Demon Arm.<ref name=\"DestructPre\">{{cite web|url=https://www.destructoid.com/you-should-be-paying-attention-to-the-darkness-ii-213431.phtml/|title=You should be paying attention to The Darkness II|first=Tara|last=Long|work=[[Destructoid]]|date=October 11, 2011|accessdate=March 7, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191028083452/https://www.destructoid.com/you-should-be-paying-attention-to-the-darkness-ii-213431.phtml|archive-date=October 28, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> The Hitman aspect consists of passive upgrades that improve the weapon's reload time and magazine size. The Execution tree allows each execution to net more benefits, such as gaining a massive amount of health, ammo or a shield.<ref name=\"DestructPre\"/> Darkness Powers and the Demon Arms grant players access to active abilities, some of which have a brief [[cooldown]] after use.<ref name=\"GRadarPre\"/><ref name=\"DestructPre\"/> These abilities include Gun Channeling, an ability that gives the player unlimited ammo and enhanced damage for a short time;<ref name=\"DestructPre\"/> Swarm, which distracts enemies; and Black Hole, which triggers a large [[area of effect]] attack that sucks enemies into a vortex.<ref name=\"GRadarPre\">{{cite web|url=https://www.gamesradar.com/darkness-ii-updated-hands-preview/|title=The Darkness II - updated hands-on preview|first=Brett|last=Elston|work=[[GamesRadar]]|date=August 28, 2011|accessdate=March 7, 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe game features a [[cooperative gameplay|cooperative multiplayer]] campaign called ''Vendettas'' that runs parallel to the main campaign and allows up to four players to play together.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.engadget.com/2011/12/06/the-darkness-2-gets-4-player-co-op-mode-in-vendettas-we-count/|title=The Darkness 2 gets 4-player co-op mode in 'Vendettas,' we count the wieldings [update: video, more screens!]|first= Christopher|last=Grant|work=[[Engadget]]|date=June 12, 2011|accessdate=March 7, 2020}}</ref> The story involves four hitmen working for Jackie as they attempt to stop the Brotherhood from obtaining the [[Spear of Destiny]]. Each character has different Darkness powers and is armed with a unique special weapon. For instance, Inugami is a character who uses a Darkness-infused samurai sword, while Shoshanna uses a blunderbuss which can shoot without bullets. Although the mode can be played solo, the experience is significantly more difficult.<ref name=\"WSPOSTcoop\">{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/business/technology/darkness-ii-announces-vendettas-co-op-mode/2011/12/06/gIQAKcUeaO_story.html|title=\u2018Darkness II\u2019 announces \u2018Vendettas\u2019 co-op mode|first=Hayley|last=Tsukayama|work=[[Washington Post]]|date=December 6, 2011|accessdate=March 7, 2020}}</ref> There is an [[arcade game|arcade]] mode called \"Hit List\" that allows players to replay certain ''Vendetta'' missions and complete challenges.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.digitalspy.com/videogames/previews/a354625/the-darkness-ii-vendettas-co-op-multiplayer-preview/|title='The Darkness II' Vendettas co-op multiplayer preview|first=Andrew|last=Laughin|work=[[Digital Spy]]|date=June 12, 2011|accessdate=March 7, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200229155657/https://www.digitalspy.com/videogames/previews/a354625/the-darkness-ii-vendettas-co-op-multiplayer-preview/|archive-date=February 29, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n==Plot==\n{{multiple image|caption_align=center|header_align=center\n | align = right\n | total_width = 320\n\n | image1 = Mike Patton with Fant\u00f4mas Quart Festival Norway 2005.jpg\n | width1 = 500 | height1 = 580\n | caption1 = [[Mike Patton]] voices the Darkness\n\n | image2 = Brian Bloom.jpg\n | width2 = 500 | height2 = 580\n | caption2 = [[Brian Bloom]] voices Jackie Estacado\n}}\n\nThe game begins two years after the events of the first game, with the player controlling Jackie Estacado ([[Brian Bloom]]), who has become head of the Franchetti family and has learned to suppress the&nbsp;Darkness ([[Mike&nbsp;Patton]]), an ancient demonic force which has inhabited Jackie's bloodline for generations. Jackie is haunted by the memory of his murdered girlfriend, Jenny Romano (Stephanie Frame), and sees apparitions of her. While relaxing at a restaurant, Jackie and his crew are attacked by a rival gang. Grievously wounded, Jackie is forced to let the Darkness out once more, restoring his powers. Aided by the Darkling (Peter Newman)\u2014a goblin-like familiar of the Darkness\u2014Jackie pursues his attackers into the subway. Jackie is mesmerized by a vision of Jenny on the tracks, only to be apparently hit by a train. He wakes up in what appears to be an asylum occupied by his crew.\n\nReawakening back into the living world, Jackie regroups with his men at his penthouse to plan a counterattack. One of Jackie's closest associates, Jimmy the Grape ([[Frank Ashmore]]), provides a lead that points to Swifty, a smaller crime boss. After subduing Swifty, he explains that a shady group he met at the Brimstone Club brothel paid him to put the hit on Jackie. Before he can reveal anything else, the Darkness brutally murders him. Vinnie ([[Rick Pasqualone]])\u2014one of Jackie's men\u2014enlists his contact at Brimstone to help them. At the club, Jackie encounters armed cultists of the Brotherhood, a secret society who ordered the hit and wish to use the Darkness for themselves. They ambush Jackie with blinding lights that inhibit the Darkness\u2019 powers, and Jackie is knocked out. Waking up, he finds himself crucified and a device (the Siphon) draining his dark power. He is greeted by Victor ([[William Salyers]]) who offers to take the Darkness from him in exchange for the lives of his family. Refusing, he loses consciousness momentarily and finds himself in Hell where the Darkness keeps Jenny's soul.\n\nAfter Jackie breaks free, Victor threatens to murder Jackie's Aunt, Sarah (Bridger Fox). As the club burns, the Darkness offers Jenny's soul in exchange for the Siphon. Jackie regroups with his men to retake the penthouse, but Jackie is shot and incapacitated by Bragg, a top Brotherhood enforcer, who murders Sarah. After being shot, Jackie awakens in a psychiatric ward where Jenny and members of his crew appear as staff and patients. They tell him that his mob stories are delusions. At Sarah's funeral, the Brotherhood launches another attack. Jackie subdues Bragg, who reveals that Victor is operating out of an abandoned theme park. Jackie is soon captured by Victor in an [[Iron maiden (torture device)|iron maiden]] and loses consciousness from blood loss. Again, he wakes in the ward, but the janitor, revealed to be his Darkling, explains that the asylum is a trap for Jackie to keep him alive and away from Jenny.\n\nJackie awakens to find that Victor has successfully drained the Darkness from him. The Darkling helps Jackie escape and retake a small portion of the Darkness. Jackie pursues Victor through a mansion once owned by Carlo Estacado, Jackie's father. Jackie learns from Victor that Carlo had promised the Darkness to the Brotherhood to ensure Jackie didn't have to suffer as he did. Reaching the attic, Jackie kills Victor and impales himself with the Siphon, regaining the Darkness and killing himself to rescue Jenny from Hell. Jackie once again wakes up in the psychiatric ward where the staff offer to take him to Jenny. The Darkling appears and sacrifices himself to help Jackie escape. Jackie reaches the roof and is confronted by Victor (appearing as a doctor), Jenny, and an orderly who attempt to convince Jackie that his life as a mob boss is a delusion and that the world in the psychiatric ward is real.\n\nOn the roof of the asylum, the player is given a choice to either have Jackie stay with Jenny in the ward, or reject the asylum and attempt to reach Hell. If the player chooses to stay, both Jenny and Jackie will head back into the asylum and slow dance to \"[[I Only Have Eyes for You]]\", and the game ends. If the player chooses to reject the asylum, Jackie will jump from the roof and fall into Hell. The Darkness, in a fit of rage, sends demons to stop Jackie from reaching Jenny, but Jackie manages to release Jenny from her bindings and the couple embrace. In a post-credits scene, Jenny is revealed to have become the new host for the [[Angelus (comics)|Angelus]], who has seen the destruction Jackie and the Darkness have caused, and states Jackie has become too powerful and leaves them trapped in Hell; leaving an enraged Jackie screaming as the screen fades out.\n\n==Development==\n[[File:Paul Jenkins, 2006.jpg|thumb|right|150px|[[Paul Jenkins (writer)|Paul Jenkins]] returned to write the game.]]\nPublisher [[2K Games]] approached Canadian developer [[Digital Extremes]] to develop ''The Darkness II'', replacing [[Starbreeze Studios]] which worked on the first game. The team worked on the title for three years. The team spent a lot of time creating the game's narrative, with [[Paul Jenkins (writer)|Paul Jenkins]] returning as the title's writer.<ref name=\"TD2 Star\">{{cite web|url=https://www.thestar.com/entertainment/2012/05/24/the_darkness_sequel_shines_light_on_london_video_game_studio.html|title=\u2018The Darkness\u2019 sequel shines light on London video game studio|first=Neil|last=Davidson|work=[[Toronto Star|The Star]]|date=May 24, 2012|accessdate=March 13, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200229153553/https://www.thestar.com/entertainment/2012/05/24/the_darkness_sequel_shines_light_on_london_video_game_studio.html|archive-date=February 29, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> According to Starbreeze's CEO Mikael Nermark, the company was not given the option of working on the sequel and was already busy working on ''[[Syndicate (2012 video game)|Syndicate]]'' when ''The Darkness II'' was announced.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.engadget.com/2011/05/17/starbreeze-giving-the-darkness-2-to-digital-extremes-was-out-of/|title=Starbreeze: Giving The Darkness 2 to Digital Extremes was out of our hands|first=David|last=Hinkle|work=[[Engadget]]|date=May 17, 2011|accessdate=March 13, 2020}}</ref>\n\nAccording to Carter, Digital Extremes agreed to assume development responsibilities as the team wanted to create a shooter with a large emphasis on the story.<ref name=\"TD2 Star\"/><ref name=\"close personal\"/> Both Jenkins and the team at Digital Extremes worked closely, with the team making adjustments to Jenkins' script to suit the gameplay.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.pcgamer.com/darkness-ii-director-talks-narrative-and-design/|title=Darkness II director talks narrative and design|first=Rob|last=Zacny|work=[[PC Gamer]]|date=September 26, 2011|accessdate=March 13, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200229153553/https://www.pcgamer.com/darkness-ii-director-talks-narrative-and-design/|archive-date=February 29, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> Carter called the narrative a \"love story\", which he felt \"[balanced] the adrenaline of the action\",<ref name=\"TD2 Star\"/> while the first part of the game's three-act plot was about \"survival\" since Jackie was attacked by an opposing mob.<ref name=\"GspotInt\">{{cite web|url=https://www.gamespot.com/articles/the-darkness-ii-qanda-demonic-power/1100-6337614/|title=The Darkness II Q&A - Demonic Power|work=[[GameSpot]]|date=September 30, 2011|accessdate=March 13, 2020}}</ref> The team spent a lot of time working on the tone of Jackie. Carter compared Jackie to [[Tony Soprano]], a \"badass\" character who has to face a lot of internal struggles.<ref name=\"close personal\">{{cite web|url=https://www.vg247.com/2011/03/04/death-is-no-option-digital-extremes-on-the-darkness-ii/|title=Death is no option: Digital Extremes on The Darkness II|first=Nathan|last=Grayson|work=[[VG 247]]|date=March 4, 2011|accessdate=March 13, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200229153556/https://www.vg247.com/2011/03/04/death-is-no-option-digital-extremes-on-the-darkness-ii/|archive-date=February 29, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> The team hoped that the story could make the players sympathize with Jackie. According to designer Tom Galt, while Jackie was a mob boss on the surface, \"in his heart he is human and a good-natured guy\".<ref name=\"art\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.siliconera.com/interview-how-shapes-and-tentacles-go-hand-in-hand-in-the-darkness-ii/|title=Interview: How Shapes And Tentacles Go Hand In Hand In The Darkness II|work=Siliconera|date=April 8, 2011|accessdate=March 13, 2020}}</ref> With the game's large focus on narrative, the Darkling was given a personality and played a huge role in the story.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://nypost.com/2011/07/29/the-darkness-ii-more-than-just-gore-but-theres-lots-of-that-as-well/|title=The Darkness II: more than just gore \u2014 but there\u2019s lots of that as well|first=William|last=Vikta|work=[[New York Post]]|date=July 29, 2011|accessdate=March 13, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200229153556/https://nypost.com/2011/07/29/the-darkness-ii-more-than-just-gore-but-theres-lots-of-that-as-well/|archive-date=February 29, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> The game does not cut to [[Third-person (video games)|third-person]] so that a limited extent of control can be granted to players even in cinematics.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.gamasutra.com/view/news/37271/Interview_The_Darkness_IIs_Sheldon_Carter_On_Cinematic_Storytelling.php|title=Interview: The Darkness II's Sheldon Carter On Cinematic Storytelling|first=Frank|last=Cifaldi|work==[[Gamasutra]]|date=September 26, 2011|accessdate=March 13, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200229153605/https://www.gamasutra.com/view/news/37271/Interview_The_Darkness_IIs_Sheldon_Carter_On_Cinematic_Storytelling.php|archive-date=February 29, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> While the game has a heavy narrative focus, all [[cutscene]]s and cinematics can be skipped for players who only want to enjoy the gameplay.<ref name=\"TD2 Star\"/>  One of the biggest requests from players of the first game was to have [[Mike Patton]] return to voice the Darkness.<ref name=\"GspotInt\"/> [[Nolan North]] served as a stand-in voice actor for Jackie during the game's pre-production, before [[Brian Bloom]] was chosen to voice the character.<ref name=\"abc\">{{cite web|url=https://www.abc.net.au/technology/articles/2012/02/13/3429221.htm|title=The Darkness II: from comic to video game and beyond|first=Jenna|last=Pitcher|work=[[Australian Broadcasting Corporation|ABC]]|date=February 13, 2012|accessdate=March 13, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140209133910/http://www.abc.net.au/technology/articles/2012/02/13/3429221.htm|archive-date=February 9, 2014|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n''The Darkness'' comic was a large inspiration for the team. The team read the comic and decided to adopt a \"graphic noir\" [[art style]], as they believed one of the main selling points to be its use of high contrast colors.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mtv.com/news/2621631/the-darkness-ii-digital-extremes-sheldon-carter-talks-the-hottest-game-of-the-year/|title=The Darkness II: Digital Extremes' Sheldon Carter Talks The Hottest Game of the Year|first=Valarie|last=Gallager|work=[[MTV]]|date=May 13, 2011|accessdate=March 13, 2020}}</ref> The team used some of the assets made by Starbreeze as a reference,<ref name=\"art\"/> and created new ones using their own internal proprietary [[game engine]] named the Evolution Engine, which powered the studio's previous game ''[[Dark Sector]]'' (2008).<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.engadget.com/2011/02/09/the-darkness-2-uses-digital-extremes-evolution-engine/|title=The Darkness 2 uses Digital Extreme's Evolution Engine|first=JC|last=Fletcher|work=[[Engadget]]|date=February 9, 2011|accessdate=March 13, 2020}}</ref> The development artists hand-painted the majority of the game's assets to create a comic book-influenced visual style, though this idea was initially met with resistance within the art team due to the huge amount of workload such an approach would create.<ref name=\"abc\"/>\n\nThe team decided to make the title more action-orientated in an attempt to differentiate itself from its predecessor.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.destructoid.com/tara-long-interviews-seth-olshfski-for-the-darkness-2-210037.phtml|title=Tara Long interviews Seth Olshfski for The Darkness 2|first=Victoria|last=Medina|work=[[Destructoid]]|date=August 27, 2011|accessdate=March 13, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150912014901/http://www.destructoid.com/tara-long-interviews-seth-olshfski-for-the-darkness-2-210037.phtml|archive-date=September 12, 2015|url-status=live}}</ref> The shooting mechanics were refined,<ref name=\"close personal\"/> and the concept of \"quad-wielding\", which allows players to engage in combat using both the Demon Arms and duel-wielding weapons, was introduced. Carter explained that they saw the Demon Arms as an opportunity to make the combat more up close and personal.<ref name=\"close personal\"/> The team changed the game's abilities to supplement this, such as turning the ability of Black Hole into a random drop from enemies.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.vg247.com/2011/07/19/the-darkness-ii-limits-black-hole-use-to-drops/|title=The Darkness II limits Black Hole use to drops|first=Brenna|last=Hillier|work=[[VG 247]]|date=July 19, 2011|accessdate=March 13, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161104011415/http://www.vg247.com/2011/07/19/the-darkness-ii-limits-black-hole-use-to-drops/|archive-date=November 4, 2016|url-status=live}}</ref> The quad-wielding mechanic enabled the combat to have more variety, allowing players to approach the same scenario with different combat styles and encourages players to experiment with different tactics. The gameplay was designed to be violent, with some execution animations being removed for being not \"extravagant\" enough.<ref name=\"TD2 Star\"/>  To ensure the game was not too easy, the team disabled Jackie's powers when he is exposed to light and created various enemy types to challenge the player in different ways.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.digitalspy.com/videogames/a361254/the-darkness-ii-interview-bringing-back-a-cult-classic/|title='The Darkness II' interview: Bringing back a cult classic|first=Andrew|last=Laughin|work=[[Digital Spy]]|date=January 20, 2012|accessdate=March 13, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200229153553/https://www.digitalspy.com/videogames/a361254/the-darkness-ii-interview-bringing-back-a-cult-classic/|archive-date=February 29, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nThe game's cooperative mode Vendetta features a story that runs parallel to the game's main narrative. The team envisioned Vendetta as a [[dark comedy]] with over-the-top characters. It is tonally very different from the main game, and the team hoped that players would use the Vendetta mode to \"blow off some steam\" after experiencing Jackie's story in the main narrative. The team used the mode to explore other characters and elements in the universe, and Jenkins has written more than 10 pages of backstory for each of the four playable characters.<ref name=\"WSPOSTcoop\"/>\n\n2K unveiled the game in May 2011.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ign.com/articles/2011/02/08/the-darkness-ii-unveiled|title=The Darkness II Unveiled|first=Martin|last=Robinson|work=[[IGN]]|date=May 9, 2012|accessdate=March 13, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190412221908/https://www.ign.com/articles/2011/02/08/the-darkness-ii-unveiled|archive-date=April 12, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> The game was initially set to be released in October the same year, though 2K announced in July 2011 that the game would be delayed until February 2012.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.gamespot.com/articles/the-darkness-ii-delayed-to-february-7/1100-6324489/|title=The Darkness II delayed to February 7|work=[[GameSpot]]|date=July 19, 2011|accessdate=March 13, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190916115907/https://www.gamespot.com/articles/the-darkness-ii-delayed-to-february-7/1100-6324489/|archive-date=September 16, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> Players who pre-ordered the game would be upgraded to the Limited Edition; which includes gameplay bonuses, illustration drawn by [[Marc Silvestri]], and digital download for ''The Darkness Origins Volume 1'' and ''Volume 2''.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.eurogamer.net/articles/2011-10-05-darkness-2-pre-order-bonus-revealed|title=Darkness 2 pre-order bonus revealed|first=Wesley|last=Yin-Poole|work=[[Eurogamer]]|date=October 5, 2011|accessdate=March 13, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181128102444/https://www.eurogamer.net/articles/2011-10-05-darkness-2-pre-order-bonus-revealed|archive-date=November 28, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> 2K provided extensive marketing for the game, launching a four-week promotion program on [[Kerrang Radio]], partnering with [[Forbidden Planet (bookstore)|Forbidden Planet]] for window displays and in-store promotions, and placing TV advertisements on both [[SyFy]] and [[Horror Channel]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.mcvuk.com/business-news/retail/the-darkness-ii-ad-plan-revealed/|title=The Darkness II ad plan revealed|work=MCVUK|date=February 8, 2012|accessdate=March 13, 2020}}</ref> A [[demoscene|demo]] for the game was released in January 2012 on [[Steam (software)|Steam]], [[Xbox Live Arcade]] and [[PlayStation Network]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.destructoid.com/the-darkness-ii-finally-has-a-demo-on-the-way-219507.phtml|title=The Darkness II finally has a demo on the way|first=Brett|last=Zeidler|work=[[Destructoid]]|date=January 11, 2011|accessdate=March 17, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150906085836/http://www.destructoid.com/the-darkness-ii-finally-has-a-demo-on-the-way-219507.phtml|archive-date=September 6, 2015|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n==Reception==\n===Critical reception===\n{{video game reviews\n| MC = (PC) 77/100<ref name=\"MCPC\">{{cite web |url=http://www.metacritic.com/game/pc/the-darkness-ii |title=The Darkness II for PC Reviews |website=[[Metacritic]] |accessdate=March 20, 2012 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120314222837/http://www.metacritic.com/game/pc/the-darkness-ii |archive-date=March 14, 2012 |url-status=live }}</ref><br/>(PS3) 79/100<ref name=\"MCPS3\">{{cite web |url=http://www.metacritic.com/game/playstation-3/the-darkness-ii |title=The Darkness II for PlayStation 3 Reviews |website=Metacritic |accessdate=March 20, 2012 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120320234559/http://www.metacritic.com/game/playstation-3/the-darkness-ii |archive-date=March 20, 2012 |url-status=live }}</ref><br/>(X360) 80/100<ref name=\"MCX360\">{{cite web |url=http://www.metacritic.com/game/xbox-360/the-darkness-ii |title=The Darkness II for Xbox 360 Reviews |website=Metacritic |accessdate=March 20, 2012 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120228191020/http://www.metacritic.com/game/xbox-360/the-darkness-ii |archive-date=February 28, 2012 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n| Destruct = 7.5/10<ref name=\"DestructRev\">{{cite web|url=https://www.destructoid.com/review-the-darkness-ii-221168.phtml|title=Review: The Darkness II|first=Conrad|last=Zimmerman|work=[[Destructoid]]|date=February 7, 2012|accessdate=March 13, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190502153823/https://www.destructoid.com/review-the-darkness-ii-221168.phtml|archive-date=May 2, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n| GI = 7/10<ref name=\"GIRev\">{{cite web|url=https://www.gameinformer.com/games/the_darkness_ii/b/xbox360/archive/2012/02/07/a-lovesick-killer-loses-his-soul.aspx|title=The Darkness II Review: A Lovesick Killer Loses His Soul|first=Andrew|last=Reiner|work=[[Game Informer]]|date=February 7, 2012|accessdate=March 13, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190824155221/https://www.gameinformer.com/games/the_darkness_ii/b/xbox360/archive/2012/02/07/a-lovesick-killer-loses-his-soul.aspx|archive-date=August 24, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n| EuroG = 7/10<ref name=\"EuroGRev\">{{cite web|url=https://www.eurogamer.net/articles/2012-02-07-the-darkness-2-review|title=The Darkness 2 Review|first=Dan|last=Whitehead|work=[[Eurogamer]]|date=February 7, 2012|accessdate=March 13, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191005062917/https://www.eurogamer.net/articles/2012-02-07-the-darkness-2-review|archive-date=October 5, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n| GRadar = {{Rating|4|5}}<ref name=\"GRadarRev\">{{cite web|url=https://www.gamesradar.com/the-darkness-ii-review/|title=The Darkness II review|first=Mikel|last=Reparaz|work=[[GamesRadar]]|date=February 7, 2012|accessdate=March 13, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191005062926/https://www.gamesradar.com/the-darkness-ii-review/|archive-date=October 5, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n| GSpot = 7/10<ref name=\"GspotRev\">{{cite web|url=https://www.gamespot.com/reviews/the-darkness-ii-review/1900-6349843|title=The Darkness II review|first=Kevin|last=VanOrd|work=[[GameSpot]]|date=February 7, 2012|accessdate=March 13, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180331095104/https://www.gamespot.com/reviews/the-darkness-ii-review/1900-6349843/|archive-date=March 31, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>\n| GameRev ={{Rating|4|5}}<ref name=\"GameRev\">{{cite web |last=Bischoff |first=Daniel R. |url=https://www.gamerevolution.com/review/54289-the-darkness-ii-xbox360-review |title=The Darkness II Review (X360) |work=[[Game Revolution]] |date=February 7, 2012 |accessdate=July 13, 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190502153829/https://www.gamerevolution.com/review/54289-the-darkness-ii-xbox360-review |archive-date=May 2, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n| IGN = 8/10<ref name=\"IGNRev\">{{cite web|url=https://www.ign.com/articles/2012/02/07/the-darkness-ii-review|title=The Darkness II review|first=Anthony|last=Gallegos|work=[[IGN]]|date=February 8, 2012|accessdate=March 13, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190515115935/https://www.ign.com/articles/2012/02/07/the-darkness-ii-review|archive-date=May 15, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n| Joystiq = {{Rating|4|5}}<ref name=\"JoystiqRev\">{{cite web|url=https://www.engadget.com/2012/02/20/the-darkness-2-review/|title=The Darkness 2 review: Shooting bullets off a list|first=Ben|last=Gilbert|work=[[Engadget]]|date=February 20, 2012|accessdate=March 13, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160531004712/http://www.engadget.com/2012/02/20/the-darkness-2-review/|archive-date=May 31, 2016|url-status=live}}</ref>\n| PCGUS = 80/100<ref name=\"PCGUSRev\">{{cite web|url=https://www.pcgamer.com/the-darkness-2-review/|title=The Darkness 2 review|first=Rich|last=McCormick|work=[[PC Gamer]]|date=February 7, 2012|accessdate=March 13, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191005062916/https://www.pcgamer.com/the-darkness-2-review/|archive-date=October 5, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n}}\n\nThe story received critical acclaim from players. Mikel Reparaz from [[GamesRadar]] described the narrative as \"part mob drama, part surreal comedy, and part supernatural revenge romance\", though he disliked the [[cliffhanger]] ending. While the game focuses on the relationship between Jackie and Jenny, Reparaz noted that the supporting characters were \"endearing\", and remarked that they were well-written and well-acted. He stated he liked the combinations of gun-play and Demon Arms gameplay, which he felt turned Jackie into \"an unstoppable dynamo of horror\". He also enjoyed the execution animations, which he felt were \"brutal\" and \"never quite get old\", though he felt that the gun-play became repetitive by the end of the game.<ref name=\"GRadarRev\"/> Anthony Gallegos from ''[[IGN]]'' felt that the story was not as immediately interesting as the first game and noted that it reused some of its predecessors' plot devices. However, he remarked that some of the scenes with Jenny were \"touching\", which made the story more \"personal\" for the player. He further commented that the game's story focus enabled the title to have better pacing.<ref name=\"IGNRev\"/> Rich McCormick from ''[[PC Gamer]]'' praised the story for being \"involving\", and that the title \"plays with concepts of [[unreliable narrator|unreliable narration]] in a way that only games allow\".<ref name=\"PCGUSRev\"/> Conrad Zimmerman from ''[[Destructoid]]'' felt the narrative was fairly average, but the game's storytelling was \"handled remarkably well\".<ref name=\"DestructRev\"/> Andrew Reiner from ''[[Game Informer]]'' remarked that unlike the original game, the title is more of a fast-paced shooter than a supernatural thriller, and he felt that the story and the characters were inferior when compared to the first game.<ref name=\"GIRev\"/> Kevin VanOrd from ''[[GameSpot]]'' praised the character development and the game's pacing. He described the story as \"unusual\" and \"creepy\", and added that the game's narrative excels when it \"plays with your expectations and has you wondering\".<ref name=\"GspotRev\"/>\n\nThe gameplay received a positive response from critics. Daniel Bischoff from ''[[Game Revolution]]'' called the gun-play \"responsive\" and the Demon Arms \"fun to control\". He particularly liked the combat variety and enemy types, which put the players in various combat scenarios. However, he was disappointed by the game's length, which lasted for only seven hours.<ref name=\"GameRev\"/> Zimmerman agreed that the game was short, but said the title was fun throughout.<ref name=\"GRadarRev\"/> Dan Whitehead from ''[[Eurogamer]]'' also praised the Demon Arms and added that it helped \"opening up combat possibilities that other shooters can't hope to compete with\". He further praised the developer for making the combat faster and refining the gameplay of the original.<ref name=\"EuroGRev\"/> Gallegos praised the combat for being \"vastly superior\" to the first game and said that Jackie's overpowered nature made the game more exciting as players could focus on fun ways to kill enemies. He also liked the skill trees, which he felt have reinvigorated the combat during the later sections of the game.<ref name=\"IGNRev\"/> McCormick noted that the game's control was not too overwhelming for players despite needing to control multiple limbs at once. However, he was disappointed by the final levels, which he felt was a \"slog\" to play through.<ref name=\"PCGUSRev\"/> Reiner praised the game for making players feel powerful, but he felt that the game was repetitive due to the lack of combat variety and remarked that combat \"relies on reflexes more than strategy\".<ref name=\"GIRev\"/> Most reviewers thought that the cooperative multiplayer mode was fun and that it provided extra gameplay for an otherwise short title,<ref name=\"DestructRev\"/><ref name=\"IGNRev\"/><ref name=\"GRadarRev\"/> though both Ben Gilbert from ''[[Joystiq]]'' and Zimmerman thought the combat not as exciting as the main game since the playable characters in the Vendetta mode do not have Demon Arms.<ref name=\"JoystiqRev\"/><ref name=\"DestructRev\"/> Whitehead noted that the mode was \"basic to the point of being crude\", though he felt the secondary story was \"enjoyable\".<ref name=\"EuroGRev\"/>\n\nThe game's presentation received mixed reviews. Gilbert praised the art direction, calling it \"gorgeous\" and \"impressive\".<ref name=\"JoystiqRev\"/> Zimmerman liked the cel-shaded graphics, which he felt was \"evocative of the comic books from which these games originate\" and made the game \"surprisingly easy to get sucked in\". Reiner, however, felt that the new art style did not capture the eerie feeling of the original game.<ref name=\"GIRev\"/> Gallegos noted that the reviewed copy suffered from [[software bugs]], broken animations, [[glitches]], and [[frame rate]] issues and felt that the game was marred by polish issues.<ref name=\"IGNRev\"/>\n\n===Sales===\nThe game was the third best-selling retail game in its week of release in the UK, surpassed by ''[[Kingdoms of Amalur: Reckoning]]'' and ''[[Final Fantasy XIII-2]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.eurogamer.net/articles/2012-02-13-uk-top-40-kingdoms-of-amalur-reckoning-beats-darkness-2|title=UK Top 40: Kingdoms of Amalur: Reckoning beats Darkness 2|first=Tom|last=Phillips|work=[[Eurogamer]]|date=February 13, 2012|accessdate=March 13, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200207090510/https://www.eurogamer.net/articles/2012-02-13-uk-top-40-kingdoms-of-amalur-reckoning-beats-darkness-2|archive-date=February 7, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{Official website|http://www.embracethedarkness.com}}\n* {{moby game|id=/darkness-ii}}\n\n{{Digital Extremes}}\n{{Witchblade}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Darkness Ii, The}}\n[[Category:2012 video games]]\n[[Category:Dark fantasy video games]]\n[[Category:Darkness in fiction]]\n[[Category:First-person shooters]]\n[[Category:MacOS games]]\n[[Category:Multiplayer and single-player video games]]\n[[Category:Organized crime video games]]\n[[Category:PlayStation 3 games]]\n[[Category:Superhero video games]]\n[[Category:Take-Two Interactive games]]\n[[Category:Video games set in New York City]]\n[[Category:Video game sequels]]\n[[Category:Video games based on Top Cow Productions]]\n[[Category:Video games developed in Canada]]\n[[Category:Video games with cel-shaded animation]]\n[[Category:Windows games]]\n[[Category:Xbox 360 games]]\n", "name_user": "OceanHok", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eDevelopment", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/The_Darkness_II"}
